<TEXT>
a former state representative got a 
6year prison term and an exstate senator was given six months at 
a halfway house monday the first sentences handed out after a 
federal probe of bribery at the statehouse 
the probe has led to bribery charges against nine lawmakers and 
drug charges against a 10th lawmaker and a lobbyist 
former state rep luther taylor brought great shame on elected 
officials and the citizens of this state such that it would cause 
all of us to hang our heads in shame for letting it come into 
being us district judge falcon hawkins said at a sentencing 
hearing 
hawkins gave taylor the maximum prison term allowed under 
federal sentencing guidelines earlier monday he sentenced former 
state sen rick lee who also was charged with selling his vote 
taylor 41 a democrat was convicted in october of six counts 
of violating the hobbs act a federal antibribery law 
he was charged with conspiring to solicit bribes and with 
accepting a total of 4300 from a lobbyistturnedfbi informant in 
exchange for supporting a bill allowing betting on horse and dog 
racing in south carolina 
taylor was taken into custody after hawkins rejected a defense 
motion to let taylor remain free on bond pending his appeal 
joel collins taylors attorney said after the hearing that 
taylor knew he might be sentenced to prison i think he accepted 
the news as well as anyone can 
lee 37 a republican avoided a prison time because of his 
cooperation with prosecutors in the investigation of statehouse 
corruption in addition to his sixmonth term in a halfway house 
lee received five years probation and will have to pay 3000 in 
restitution 
federal sentencing guidelines would have allowed hawkins to 
sentence lee to up to 27 months in prison 
lee and three other former legislators pleaded guilty in august 
to accepting a 2000 bribe from a lobbyist for his work on behalf 
of the parimutuel betting bill the four all had resigned from the 
legislature when they were indicted in august 
im very appreciative of the judges sentencing and the work 
my attorney did lee said afterward im very thankful at being 
sentenced to a halfway house where i can work and contribute to my 
familys wellbeing that in itself is a blessing 
a fifth exlegislator pleaded guilty to a cocaine charge and 
also awaits sentencing 
four other house members await trials later this month and next 
lobbyist james brown v indicted on a marijuana charge died last 
week of complications from lung disease 
