<TEXT>
the magellan spacecraft found evidence that 
volcanoes may be erupting to this day on venus and that they gushed 
an australiasized flood of lava in recent geological times 
the spacecrafts new radar pictures of the cloudcovered planet 
suggest that at any given time venus is active in several 
regions said roger phillips a scientist at southern methodist 
university in dallas venus is not dead 
magellans pictures show there are no meteorite impact craters 
in an australiasized portion of the planet phillips said monday 
during a meeting of the american geophysical union 
that means the huge area is covered by lava that was deposited 
sometime within the last tens of millions of years relatively 
recent in geological terms phillips said 
it raises the likelihood venus is still active he added 
magellan hasnt yet found direct proof that volcanoes are 
erupting today on the planet to accomplish that magellan must fly 
over the same parts of venus twice and look for differences caused 
by any active lava flows 
and that wont happen until next spring 
magellan was launched from a shuttle in may 1989 went into 
orbit around venus on aug 10 and started maing maps and pictures 
in september 
as of monday magellan had orbited venus 847 times it bounces 
radar off the planets surface to make images 
