<TEXT>
rossinis semiramide returned to the 
metropolitan opera where it was last heard in 1895 
mezzosoprano marilyn horne portrying a man and bass samuel 
ramey are masters of this kind of florid singing with enough vocal 
flexibility to trill three notes where operas written later would 
have one note 
despite the debut of lella cuberli with her delicate voice in 
the title role friday it was hornes and rameys night especially 
hornes she conveyed not only lush secure sound but the assurance 
she knows what the music in this 1823 opera is all about 
cuberli is from austin texas and a graduate of southern 
methodist university she has been specializing in rossini roles 
mainly in europe and regularly at la scala since 1975 semiramide 
gives her one of the most beautiful arias in opera 
chris merritt a tall large tenor from oklahoma city who 
attended oklahoma city university also made his met debut he has 
specialized in bel canto operas by rossini bellini and donizetti 
mostly in europe his voice is warm and very attractive in its 
middle register it thins out when he sings high though he can hit 
the top notes 
young ok shin from korea also made her met debut 
the vocal range required for performers in semiramide makes 
it pointless to present if an adequate cast cant be assembled 
this cast is better than just capable in voice style and stamina 
gaetano rossi based the libretto on a tragedy by voltaire 
semiramide queen of babylon had a prince ramey kill her husband 
15 years before he hopes to become king semiramide falls in love 
