a bird thought to have become extinct in 
recent decades has been turning up on the dinner plates of farmers 
in vietnam the world wildlife fund for nature says 
three of the rare birds known as vietnamese or vo quys 
pheasants are currently in captivity in hanoi the vietnamese 
capital according to the latest issue of world wildlife fund news 
vietnamese scientists called a search for the bird after hunters 
in northcentral vietnam reported trapping and eating them 
regularly 
local farmers were asked to keep alive any pheasants caught 
bearing resemblance to the rare species 
the pheasant was first discovered in 1964 by vo quy a prominent 
ornithologist who has spearheaded conservation efforts in vietnam 
it was thought to have become extinct in the years that followed 
quy was quoted by world wildlife fund news as saying reserves 
covering the birds remaining area of forest habitat should be set 
up urgently to ensure its survival 
the three captive birds were seen at the hanoi zoo by elizabeth 
kemf author of the article and a recent book on environmental 
problems in vietnam 
quy also expressed concern for the fate of vietnams other 
species of pheasant eight of which are endangered 
hunting logging and clearing of land for agriculture were cited 
as responsible for the decline of all pheasant species in vietnam 
the switzerlandbased world wildlife fund deals with 
environmental issues around the world 
