in order for the company to grow it would be a good move 
he said 
tourism here was down even before there were signs of a national 
recession which only makes things worse said roy l pearson 
director of the college of william and marys bureau of business 
research 
he said 1990 has been the third worst year for williamsburg 
tourism exceeded only by the recession years of 1974 and 1982 
colonial williamsburg opened in 1932 after a sixyear 
restoration project paid for by john d rockefeller jr about 1 
million visitors are expected this year down from 117 million in 
1989 
daylong passes cost 21 to 2450 for adults and provide 
entrance to various exhibits and restored buildings there are also 
numerous restaurants and shops 
williamsburgs tourism growth ended prior to any slowdown 
nationally pearson wrote in his williamsburg business index 
if we were that vulnerable when others were doing well then we 
truly are at risk now that the external economy has stopped 
growing 
