<TEXT>
computer purchasing officials in the navy and 
possibly in other government agencies have too cozy a relationship 
with privatesector contractors such as ibm corp says a 
congressional report issued today 
the house government operations committee report says there 
should be stronger regulations and better oversight to eliminate 
bias in awarding computer contracts 
the report follows a yearlong probe touched off by complaints 
in 1988 from six ibm competitors who said they had been frozen out 
of the navys multibilliondollar computer market 
through a combination of agency malfeasance and the dominance 
of one vendor the fair and open system contemplated by congress 
has been torpedoed in navy computer procurement the report 
says 
it details a tangled web of agency and contractor abuse 
improprieties and illegalities said rep john conyers dmich 
the committee chairman its an old story that when the rule of 
law breaks down it is the strong who benefit 
the committee said its investigation had been broadened to 
include other agencies including the national institutes of 
health the national aeronautics and space administration and the 
treasury department all have large complex computer systems and 
are major computer equipment buyers 
the report says ibm appears for the most part not to be 
responsible for the bizarre navy acquisition system but merely 
its willing beneficiary 
former naval officer john cahill testified during one hearing 
that his commanding officer while attending a free ibm promotional 
training seminar telephoned cahill and ordered him to change our 
procurement strategy to go after a new ibm technology the report 
said cahill said he refused and awarded the contract to another 
company 
the report described the officers participation in the ibm 
program as clearly improper at least 128 navy officials were 
trained by ibm in san jose calif between 1985 and 1987 
navy undersecretary j daniel howard in a sept 7 letter to 
conyers said ibms training of cahills superior was not an 
illegal gratuity because ibm did not win the contract it sought 
but howard acknowledged there was an appearance of impropriety 
the general services administration the agency responsible for 
overseeing government purchases of automated data processing 
equipment should take the lead in fixing the system to eliminate 
bias the report said 
it said the gsa should review training programs and seminars 
offered by computer contractors to determine whether they are 
proper for government employees and should issue clear guidelines 
on contacts between federal buyers and contractors 
gsa should review government computer purchases more frequently 
and carefully the report said agencies cannot be trusted to 
follow the rules and regulations governing computer 
acquisitions it said 
navy spokesman lt james wood would not comment beyond saying 
that the navy had cooperated with the committee during the 
investigation 
ibm spokesman mark holcomb said the company endorsed the 
proposed review of policies on relations between the government and 
privatesector computer companies 
but he said it would be unfair if congress in ordering such a 
review implied that ibms dealings with the navy had been 
improper 
we did not do anything wrong holcomb said if they want 
to change the regulations after the fact we will comply but were 
in complete compliance with existing regulations and have been 
all along 
