with pmobitcopland bjt 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
leonard bernsteins visit to aaron coplands 
studio a half century ago opened the door on a friendship between 
two composers who helped helped put american classical music on the 
world map 
on sunday copland joined bernstein in death 
in life they had created what a composer called the american 
sound 
they were made for each other said the pulitzer 
prizewinning composer david del tredici aaron wrote the music 
and lenny was its wonderful interpreter aaron was the moses and 
lenny was the aaron 
william schuman who with bernstein and copland formed what 
schuman called a triumvirate of american composers said copland 
believed in the validity of american music that we were not 
inferior to our european cousins 
copland and bernstein first met when the young lenny in his 
20s and fresh from harvard showed up at coplands new york studio 
door opposite lincoln center 
copland opened the door bernstein introduced himself and then 
he just sat down and played variations a work by copland said 
del tredici who claims copland as his mentor 
del tredici recalled weekends 20 years ago spent at coplands 
home near new york which he described as a very copland kind 
of place spacious comfortable 
there was no vanity in him he was very endearing he said 
adding that copland didnt care much about food or a fancy 
home 
he was generous to everyone around him and under him and 
uncomplicated said del tredici usually geniuses are 
selfcentered and i thought how can a man be a genius and still 
be so nice 
the downtoearth approach translated into musical artistry that 
drew on american folk tunes and jazz 
like most sons of immigrants he wanted to be more american 
than the americans said del tredici 
at coplands last birthday celebration two weeks ago he ate 
apple pie which he preferred to cake surrounded by old friends 
copland read messages from young people from fifthgraders in 
arkansas to teenagers in arizona 
he was not the least pretentious if you didnt know he was 
one of the greatest artists of the century you would never suspect 
it with his wonderful ruddy laugh said schuman 
he had a uniquely american voice and was able to express in 
his music particularly american sensibilities using substantially 
the language of european serious music said kenneth haas 
managing director of the boston symphony 
copland taught at the orchestras tanglewood music school in 
lenox mass for 25 years and was head of the faculty there when 
he stepped down in 1970 
he lived a very productive 90 years haas said happily 
we will have his music to appreciate even though we dont have him 
any more 
