<TEXT>
the food and drug administration today 
approved the first nonprescription drug to treat vaginal yeast 
infections which afflict nearly threefourths of all women at 
least once in their lifetimes 
availability of the drug clotrimazole for nonprescription 
sales will spare many women the inconvenience and expense of going 
to a doctor to get a prescription to treat the common infections 
the fda said 
clotrimazole is highly effective and carries a minimal risk 
said dr carl peck director of the fdas center for drug 
evaluation and research adding that it has a 10year history of 
safe prescription use 
fda has concluded that the switch of this drug to 
nonprescription sale will benefit women especially those with 
recurring infections who will be able to treat themselves he 
said 
peck said that as long as the infection is initially diagnosed 
by a doctor a woman can recognize the symptoms and treat herself 
without needing a prescription 
labeling on the drugs package will say if this is the first 
time you are suffering from vaginal itch and discomfort please 
consult your physician 
in a small number of cases use of the drug can cause allergic 
reactions including burning and a rash more rarely it has caused 
abdominal cramps and bloating the fdas cruzan said 
women who are pregnant are advised not to use the product except 
under a physicians supervision 
vaginal yeast infection or candidiasis is an overgrowth of a 
naturally occurring fungus called candida the overabundance occurs 
when the bodys natural balance of bacteria is upset this often 
occurs with antibiotics or birth control pills 
when the yeast overgrows the resulting infection causes itching 
and burning sometimes with a discharge and soreness 
however other conditions including sexually transmitted 
diseases can cause similar symptoms which is why a woman should 
get an initial diagnosis by a physician said fda spokeswoman susan 
cruzan 
a brochure that will be sold with the product will advise women 
to continue treatment for seven consecutive days even if the 
infection appears to have cleared up before then if signs of the 
infection do not clear up in three days the brochure advises the 
woman should see a physician 
the drug which will be available as a vaginal suppository or as 
a cream is made by scheringplough in kenilworth nj and will 
be sold under the trade name gynelotrimin 
nearly 22 million cases of vaginal yeast infections are reported 
annually the company said and nearly 75 percent of all women will 
experience at least one infection 
</TEXT>
