<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that a federal 
anticounterfeiting law may be used to crack down on the sale of 
used cars with phony mileage readings 
by 53 vote the court upheld the conviction of raymond j 
moskal manager of a pennsylvania car dealership sentenced under 
the law to six months in prison 
moskal was convicted of taking part in a scheme in which car 
odometers were turned back and ownership titles listing the lower 
mileages were obtained in virginia 
that process called title washing is covered by a 1939 
federal law that makes it a crime to ship falsely made 
documents across state lines said justice thurgood marshall for 
the court 
our conclusion that falsely made encompasses genuine 
documents containing false information is supported by congress 
purpose in enacting the law he said title washes involve 
precisely the sort of fraudulent activities that are dispersed 
among several states in order to elude state detection 
justice antonin scalia in a dissenting opinion said the ruling 
creates a dangerous precedent because the court is interpreting a 
law in a way that seems to conflict with the dictionary meaning of 
words 
falsely made is not the same thing as false he said 
a forged memorandum is falsely made scalia said a 
memorandum that contains erroneous information is simply false the 
temptation to stretch the law to fit the evil is an ancient one 
and it must be resisted 
he was joined by justices sandra day oconnor and anthony m 
kennedy 
justice david h souter did not take part in the ruling 
moskal was convicted with al davis owners of the wholesale car 
dealership in manheim pa that moskal managed and dennis smith 
owner of a dealership in chesapeake va davis and smith did not 
appeal to the high court 
prosecutors said the ownership certificates from davis 
dealership were shipped to contacts in virginia who applied for 
titles in that state with the phony lower mileage figures 
the virginia titles then were sent back to davis and he 
distributed them to area dealers to sell with the used cars 
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals upheld the convictions of 
the three men 
but federal appeals courts elsewhere in the nation have struck 
down similar convictions on grounds the federal law did not cover 
odometer tampering 
the case is moskal vs us 89964 
</TEXT>
