the government on monday decided to 
stiffen the punishment of kidnappingsffor ransom raising the 
sentence from life in prison to death by hanging to try to halt the 
rising number of abductions 
finance minister sartaj aziz told reporters the decision was 
taken at a cabinet meeting 
there has been a rising tide of kidnappings aziz said 
strictest punishment is needed 
pakistans criminal law called for life imprisonment and 
forefeiture of property for kidnapping but that will be amended to 
include the death penalty aziz said 
prime minister nawaz sharif announced the plan three weeks ago 
prompting speculation that the harsher punishment was aimed at asif 
ali zardari the husband of ousted prime minister benazir bhutto 
zardari is in jail in karachi for his alleged role in the 
kidnapping and extortion of a pakistaniborn british businessman 
zardari twice has been refused bail 
the government denies anyone is the target of the new law 
aziz said the amendment will be introduced before the national 
assembly the lawmaking lower house of parliament for 
ratification later this month 
kidnappings for ransom has increased dramatically in the past 
two years in southern sindh province especially in karachi the 
countrys largest city and its financial and industrial center 
scores of wealthy businessmen and their familes have been the 
main targets most have been released after their families paid 
huge ransoms 
politicians had blamed the crime on what is popularly known as 
the kalashnikov and heroin culture a referrence to the 
automatic rifle that has flooded pakistan during the war in 
