<DOCNO> AP901203-0079 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today resolved conflicting 
rulings by federal appeals courts around the country over the 
deadline federal employees face when suing over alleged onthejob 
bias 
the court by a 62 vote said such suits against federal 
employers sometimes may be allowed even if the 30day deadline is 
missed 
some appeals courts had disallowed such waivers for suits 
against the federal government while allowing more deadline 
flexibility in suits against private employers 
but by a separate 71 vote the court ruled that the 30day 
deadline begins when the office of the suing persons lawyer 
receives a righttosue letter from the federal equal employment 
opportunity commission 
there had been some confusion in lower courts about whether the 
30day period began to run only when the suing persons themselves 
or their lawyers not their lawyers office received notice of the 
right to sue 
writing for the high court in a texas case chief justice 
william h rehnquist said federal courts need not throw out all 
such bias lawsuits filed past the deadline 
but rehnquist added that no waiver is required when the delay 
was caused by a lawyers absence from the law office where the 
righttosue notice was received 
the decision killed a suit by shirley w irwin a handicapped 
former employee of the veterans administration medical center in 
waco texas 
irwins suit said the va fired him illegally in 1986 
justices byron r white and thurgood marshall voted to make the 
30day deadline apply to all suits by federal employees regardless 
of the reason for delay 
justice john paul stevens voted to have the 30day deadline 
begin to run only when the suing employees themselves receive 
notice of their right to sue 
the case is irwin vs va 895867 
 
 
</TEXT>
