<TEXT>
the federal government and oil 
producers have resolved an environmental dispute that had stalled 
production at part of a vast alaskan oilfield near prudhoe bay 
the army corps of engineers the main opponent of the project 
agreed friday to a plan in which arco bp exploration and exxon 
would spend an estimated 50 million in the drilling area to ease 
fish migration in the beaufort sea 
the agreement clears the way for production to begin within two 
years at the point mcintyre field where the oil companies own 
rights to an estimated 300 million barrels production from point 
mcintyre and the nearby lisburne field could reach 100000 barrels 
a day by 1994 said al greenstein a spokesman at arcos 
headquarters in los angeles 
our agreement recognizes that environmental quality and 
economic reality are both important in north slope oil and gas 
decisions said col william w kakel alaska district engineer 
for the corps 
officials from the energy department helped mediate the dispute 
in an effort to increase domestic oil output to help make up for 
the loss of 200000 barrels a day of kuwaiti oil following the aug 
2 iraqi invasion 
production had been delayed because of concerns that existing 
gravel causeways that extended from land into the beaufort sea 
threatened fish that migrate in the coastal waters of northern 
alaska the roadbeds were built for exploration drilling at the 
point mcintyre field and the nearby endicott field 
federal officials said the causeways appeared to raise salt 
concentrations and the water temperature to levels that could be 
harmful to the arctic char broad whitefish and other fish relied 
upon by commercial fishermen 
oil industry officials have said years of monitoring programs on 
the causeways did not indicate any adverse effects to the fish 
but they agreed to spend 50 million to clear several water 
passages in the gravel roadbeds the agreement calls for 650 
additional feet of openings in the prudhoe bay west dock and 
endicott gravel causeways 
the agreement enables oil companies to move ahead with 
production and avoids years of dispute and possible litigation 
said brian davies a vice president for development at bp 
the causeway work could take as long as five years said bp 
spokesman paul laird 
output at the lisburne field which is already in production is 
40000 barrels a day greenstein said the combined output from the 
lisburne and point mcintyre fields will exceed 60000 barrels a day 
when output from point mcintyre begins by late summer in 1992 and 
could 100000 barrels a day after a planned expansion in 1993 
about 13 million barrels a day are produced each day from 
prudhoe bay fields 
