<TEXT>
former east german leader erich honecker insists 
he is not guilty of charges that he issued shoottokill orders at 
the berlin wall his lawyer said monday 
for the third straight day soviet officials blocked the arrest 
of honecker who has taken refuge at a soviet military hospital in 
the woods south of berlin soviet doctors believe he is seriously 
ill an interpreter said 
berlin justice officials issued an arrest warrant friday two 
days before a united germany held its first free elections in 58 
years they said they based the warrant on new documents recently 
uncovered that incriminate honecker 
honecker faces charges that he signed shoottokill orders at 
the berlin wall the border between former east and west germany 
but german police cannot arrest honecker without soviet 
permission to enter the hospital which is guarded by armed 
soldiers the soviets have indicated they are holding their former 
ally on humanitarian grounds 
in moscow foreign ministry spokesman vitaly churkin told a news 
conference nobody knows what will happen with honecker and how 
the situation will be resolved 
the decision to get mr honecker to a soviet hospital had to 
do with his state of health and we would like to believe that the 
german side will also be guided first of all by principles of 
humanism churkin said 
the warrant specifically links honecker to the deaths of four 
people killed while trying to flee his repressive regime before it 
was toppled in last years peaceful revolution about 200 people 
died trying to escape from east germany during the 28year 
existence of the berlin wall 
wolfgang ziegler one of honeckers defense lawyers told the 
adn news agency that his client insisted he was not guilty 
the agency said ziegler had lodged a protest against the arrest 
warrant on grounds that honecker cannot be punished for alleged 
crimes committed under east german laws the east german legal 
system ceased to exist when the former communist state acceded to 
west germany on oct 3 and west german laws took effect 
honecker 78 was transferred earlier monday to a cardiology 
unit at the soviet military hospital in beelitz 20 miles south of 
berlin he took refuge there in april 
adn quoted a soviet interpreter as saying red army doctors 
considered honeckers condition serious one doctor diagnosed 
honecker as having high blood pressure the agency quoted igor 
molotkin the interpreter as saying 
honeckers lawyers maintain that he is too sick to stand trial 
german justice officials say they have no way of verifying 
honeckers state of health until the soviets let them into the 
hospital 
an official at the soviet embassy in bonn on monday refused to 
comment on a report that talks were under way between german and 
soviet officials on handing over honecker whose testimony could be 
potentially damaging to moscow 
honecker in coments published in november by the european a 
british weekly newspaper complained that he was brought down from 
power by intriguers 
later the same month he said he was toppled on oct 18 1989 
because of a soviet conspiracy according to a report published in 
the berlin wochenpost weekly newspaper 
the soviet union and the other three victorious world war ii 
powers relinquished special rights over the two german states in 
agreements that restored german sovereignty 
but the oct 12 germansoviet agreement on the withdrawal of red 
army forces stationed in eastern germany assures the soviets 
control of their military bases 
