<TEXT>
painter and art critic antonio dacosta 
who introduced surrealism to portugal and became one of the 
countrys leading artists has died he was 76 
dacosta died sunday in a hospital in paris where he had lived 
intermittently since 1947 the cause of death was not given 
president mario soares on monday called dacosta a personality 
without equal in portuguese culture a painter of extraordinary 
resources and a most fine sensibility 
born in the azores island town of angra do heroismo in 1914 
dacosta moved to lisbon at 21 to study art he was inspired by 
french and spanish surrealists especially the spanish artist 
salvador dali 
dacosta held the first surrealist exhibition in portugal in 
1940 
in 1949 he abandoned painting to work as a journalist and art 
critic in paris for portuguese and brazilian newspapers 
dacosta returned to painting in 1975 
his early works showed a dramatic fluid use of forms and 
colors later works were more abstract with gentler color use 
influenced by the rural landscapes of the azores 
a major retrospective of his work was held to critical acclaim 
at lisbons calouste gulbenkian museum in 1988 
dacosta is survived by his wife miriam and their two children 
funeral plans were not immediately announced 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

