<TEXT>
the publisher of consumer reports is urging the 
food and drug administration to halt the sale of milk from cows 
being treated with a genetically engineered growth hormone 
critics have repeatedly raised questions about possible health 
risks associated with milk containing the hormone but the fda and 
many others have argued that bovine growth hormone as its called 
has no effect on human health 
the hormone is given to cows to boost milk production some 
critics have argued that it could have a harmful economic effect by 
boosting milk production at a time when there is no shortage of 
milk 
it has not yet been approved by the fda but in 1985 the agency 
ruled that milk from cows treated with the hormone could be sold 
consumers union which publishes the magazine called on the fda 
to reopen its investigation of the human safety of the hormone 
while it pursues its review of the hormones effects on animal 
health 
we see virtually no benefits to the average consumer from the 
use of this drug michael k hansen the reports author said 
its use is unlikely to result in lower milk prices to consumers 
in fact its use may cost consumers tax dollars that the federal 
government must spend to buy up dairy surpluses 
four companies produce growth hormone american cyanamid eli 
lilly monsanto and upjohn 
in august the fda released a review of more than 120 studies to 
support its contention that the hormone is safe for human 
consumption a week earlier an article in the journal of the 
american medical association also found the hormone to be safe 
yet critics have continued to raise questions 
last week jeremy rifkin one of the most outspoken critics 
sued the national dairy board for what he said was illegal 
promotion of the hormone before it has been approved by the fda 
he also petitioned the agency to immediately halt any 
promotion of this product by fda officials and to immediately 
rescind the use of this product in the marketplace until it is 
approved 
on monday he filed another petition asking the agency to halt 
sales recall milk produced by hormonetreated cows and establish a 
longterm independent research program on the hormones safety 
william grigg and fda spokesman said the agency has determined 
that the hormone is not active in humans and occurs normally in 
milk in amounts comparable to those found in milk from treated 
cows 
</TEXT>
