<TEXT>
the supreme court said monday it will decide 
whether police who have an owners permission to search a car must 
get a court warrant before opening any containers inside the 
vehicle 
the justices agreed to review a florida supreme court ruling 
that court warrants are needed before police open containers found 
in the cars interior other than in the trunk 
in a 1982 decision the nations highest court ruled that police 
can search even closed containers within a cars trunk any time an 
officer has reasonable cause to believe the car contains drugs 
weapons or other contraband 
no warrant is needed for such searches of containers found in 
the trunk the court said in 1982 
the justices now must decide probably by july whether that 
ruling applies to consentual searches conducted inside that part of 
the car where the driver and passengers sit the florida court said 
the 1982 ruling did not apply 
the state courts ruling barred prosecutors from using as trial 
evidence cocaine found by a miami policeman in a car owned by enio 
and luz jimeno during a 1989 search 
officer frank trujillo became suspicious of the car driven by 
enio jimeno and followed it until it made an illegal turn trujillo 
then stopped the car and asked to search the inside for drugs 
jimeno consented and trujillos search turned up a brown paper 
bag on the floor on the front passenger side 
trujillo did not ask for permission to open the bag before doing 
so and found cocaine inside 
a state trial judge granted the jimenos request to exclude the 
cocaine as evidence against them and the florida supreme court 
upheld that ruling 
attorney general robert butterworth then appealed contending 
that police authority to conduct warrantless car searches when 
given consent is just as broad as a search based on warrant or 
probable cause 
lawyers for the jimenos had urged the justices to reject 
butterworths appeal 
the case is florida vs jimeno 90622 
</TEXT>
