national institute of mental health filed a federal lawsuit 
contending that a male superior harassed her because she was female 
and fired her in 1989 before she could complete the third year of a 
fellowship program 
the suit filed in us district court in maryland also alleged 
that jensvold was denied opportunities for research and writing 
provided to male medical fellows and that a male superior tried to 
destroy her academic career 
a spokeswoman for nimh said officials had not seen the suit and 
would have no immediate comment 
the suit said that when jensvold worked in the menstrually 
related mood disorder clinic at nimh she was the only woman 
physician in the program set up to study premenstrual syndrome 
i was never accepted by the male physicians who were in charge 
of my program jensvold said in a statement 
she said male physicians constantly denigrated women who had 
preceded her saying they did not deserve any credit for work they 
had done and that they had been pushed out because they could not 
get along with male colleagues 
earlier this year a study by the general accounting office 
congress investigative arm found that the national institutes of 
health has had little success with its fouryear effort to include 
more women in government research of diseases and their treatments 
nih and nimh have recently come under serious criticism for 
failing to includ women as research subjects jensvold said 
now it is clear that they are also excluding women as 
researchers the effect of these two things on womens health is 
very destructive 
