the military rebellion that 
erupted monday is the fourth since 1987 staged by dissident 
soldiers the others were 
in april 1987 about 130 officers and noncommissioned officers 
led by former lt col aldo rico a commando and falklands veteran 
holed up at an infantry school in suburban buenos aires rico 
sought amnesty for officers accused of human rights abuse during 
the 197683 military regime 
president raul alfonsin secured ricos surrender and later 
pushed a law through congress that absolved most officers below the 
rank of general of rights violations charges rico was placed under 
house arrest 
there were no deaths or serious injuries in the uprising 
in january 1988 rico fled house arrest and flew to an infantry 
garrison about 440 miles north of buenos aires joined by about 200 
supporters he accused the government of failing to fully meet 
demands made during his first rebellion loyal forces surrounded 
the garrison and rico surrendered he was imprisoned and cashiered 
several army generals retired and military pay was increased 
in that uprising two loyalist soldiers were wounded when their 
truck ran over a mine 
in december 1988 col mohamed ali seineldin also a commando 
and falklands veteran took over an army arsenal in buenos aires 
demanding that the government recognize the armys role in ending 
leftist terrorism and fighting the falklands war surrounded by 
loyalist forces seineldin and his men surrendered 
one civilian was killed and several wounded when fired on during 
a demonstration outside the occupied arsenal 
president carlos menem who took office on july 8 1989 
pardoned seineldin and other uprising participants seineldin was 
forced to retire 
he currently is serving a 60day jail sentence ordered after he 
wrote a letter to menem outside the chain of command criticizing 
army leaders for failing to live up to promises made following 
previous rebellions 
rico released from prison began forming a rightwing 
nationalist political organization and said he planned to seek 
public office 
