<DOCNO> AP901203-0114 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is a list of the most contentious issues to 
be resolved at the trade talks in brussels 
agriculture the linchpin of the talks declared aim 
substantial progressive reductions in agricultural support and 
protection over a sustained period of time the united states 
wants cuts of 75 percent in internal supports and import barriers 
and 90 percent in export subsidies over ten years the 12nation 
european community has offered a 30 percent cut in internal 
supports by 1995 no negotiating text has been sent to brussels 
services aim is to set up a general agreement on trade in 
services to liberalize trade in the 680 billion sector just as 
the general agreement on tariffs and trade has opened markets in 
goods the united states wants a new agreement to allow the 
continuation of bilateral accords most others say benefits granted 
to one country must apply to all countries the negotiating text is 
littered with brackets and an annex on financial services is left 
blank 
market access aim is to reduce overall import tariffs by at 
least one third many countries have been slow in making offers 
leading to us threats to withdraw some cuts it has proposed 
washington offered cuts averaging 43 percent leaving high tariffs 
on textiles and other sensitive products the ec proposed flatrate 
cuts excluding agricultural products the text is awaiting the 
outcome of bilateral talks many negotiators say the issue is as 
difficult as agriculture and services 
antidumping aim is to revise the existing gatt antidumping 
code which authorizes duties against dumping goods on world 
markets at artificially low prices japan and southeast asian 
countries want tighter restrictions to prevent the west from using 
such duties merely to protect inefficient industries the west 
wants new measures against the evasion of duties there is no 
agreed negotiating text 
trade related investment measures aim is to draw up rules on 
measures that governments apply to investors such as the insistence 
on use of local materials the united states considers that all 
such measures distort trade and should be controlled or banned the 
third world says they are part of national development policies and 
should not be regulated by gatt there is no agreed negotiating 
text 
subsidies aim is to draw up rules governing both state aids 
to industry and measures to counter exports subsidized in this 
manner washington wants tough rules against subsidies countries 
such as canada and southeast asian nations say there should be more 
restrictions on counterveiling duties 90 percent of which are 
imposed by the united states the chairman of the group has drafted 
a text but the it has not been officially accepted 
trade related aspects of intellectual property rights aim is 
to agree on new rules on copyright trademarks patents etc there 
are divisions among industrialized nations on patent standards 
talks also are marked by a northsouth split on whether 
pharmaceutical products should be exempt from patent rules to 
enable continued cheap access for the third world there is no 
agreement on how any new rules should be enforced 
textiles aim is to phase out the 16yearold international 
multifiber arrangement which restricts exports through bilateral 
agreements and bring it within gatt rules there are differences 
between third world exporters which want swift liberalization and 
industrialized countries with their own textile industries 
outstanding issues include the scope of products to be covered the 
length of any phaseout and whether or not to implement safeguard 
measures against a sudden surge of imports during the transition 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

