monday and a vote was not expected until tuesday at the earliest 
in california deukmejians plan would cut 600 million in 
public school funding and 200 million from an income tax credit 
for renters as well as freeze state hiring and purchases in a 75 
billion budget deukmejian says his budget cuts would give 
california a cushion against worsening tax revenues 
deukmejian said he would like california legislators to approve 
his plan before he leaves office in january many legislators 
particularly majority democrats would rather wait until republican 
govelect pete wilson takes office jan 7 
new york and california have suffered sharp declines in tax 
revenues and cuomo has blamed his states problems on a struggling 
national economy 
california had a 13 billion reserve that deukmejian expects to 
be depleted by the end of the budget year new york has no such 
reserve and the cuomo administration has been trying to slow down 
spending for months 
