one day after triumphing in allgerman 
elections chancellor helmut kohl on monday began talks with 
coalition allies on forming a new government and prepared to tackle 
enormous problems facing the new germany 
his centerright coalition swept to victory in sundays 
parliamentary balloting the first in a united germany since 1932 
but kohl had little time to bask in the glory 
on monday the chancellor began talks with his christian 
democratic unions current governing partners their bavarian 
sister party the christian social union and the centrist free 
democrats 
he was hit by an ultimatum from the free democrats which made 
more gains in the elections than any other party they said they 
would reenter the coalition only if kohl agreed that companies in 
former east germany should pay lower taxes than those in former 
west germany 
no lowtax area no vote for the chancellor said otto 
lambsdorff chairman of the free democrats arguing that would be 
an important move toward encouraging badly needed investment in 
eastern germany 
kohl has said he opposes such a move contending it is 
unnecessary on monday he refused to discuss the issue in public 
and suggested his coalition partners do the same 
i am of the old school that believes in talking first and 
going public later kohl said 
he also said he would not be put under time pressure by 
anyone in forming a new cabinet he said he couldnt promise the 
coalition negotiations would be concluded before christmas 
kohls day began with an announcement from economics minister 
helmut haussmann who said he was quitting the cabinet amid what 
german television claimed was growing criticism over his handling 
of the economy 
haussmann was a major force in putting together the economic and 
monetary union of west and east germany in july a crucial step 
toward full unification on oct 3 he gave no reason for quitting 
later the head of germanys poerful central bank slammed 
kohls plans to borrow 100 billion next year to finance 
unification 
in an interview with stern magazine karl otto poehl said the 
proposed sum was too high and demanded instead greater spending 
cuts 
later kohls christian democrats met to discuss coalition 
negotiations and the vast problems the new government must tackle 
at a press conference kohl counted off some of those issues he 
said important decisions needed to be made on ways to slash 
government spending and raise further revenues to rebuild eastern 
germany 
the chancellor has insisted he will not increase taxes to come 
up with extra revenues for the massive reconstruction job but he 
has not disclosed just where the money will come from 
kohl could run up against opposition from his coalition partners 
over such issues 
the chancellor also said his government faces the huge task of 
cleaning up former east germany which has severe pollution 
problems 
the legacy of east germanys deposed communist government 
is especially grave in this area kohl said 
germany will also have to take on new global responsibilities 
that befit what is seen as its growing political and economic 
stature on the world stage kohl said 
but he indicated germany will not likely be able to quickly make 
the constitutional changes necessary to allow the deployment of 
german troops in the persian gulf or elsewhere outside nato areas 
we will discuss this within the coalition and with the 
opposition social democrats he said 
many social democrats oppose constitutional changes 
kohl came under sharp international criticism in august when he 
declined to send german troops to the gulf but under germanys 
constitution german troops cannot be deployed in nonnato areas 
kohl has since said he favors the appropriate constitutional 
amendment 
the big losers in sundays elections were the social democrats 
the main opposition party and the greens both leftist parties 
had criticized kohls swift pace of unification and accused his 
christian democrats of underplaying the cost of bringing the east 
up to the standard of the west 
the social democrats gained 13 parliamentary seats finishing 
with 239 
western germanys greens europes mostestablished ecology 
movement were voted out of parliament their sister branch in 
former east germany snared only eight seats 
kohls christiahristian social union alliance 
increased its strength from 305 to 313 seats in the 656member 
n democrat and cparliament 
however they failed to attain the absolute majority that would 
have allowed them to govern without the free democrats which 
increased their seats in parliament from 57 to 79 
