<DOCNO> AP901203-0124 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the music world monday mourned the death of 
composer aaron copland the son of immigrants whose genius earned 
him the title dean of american music 
copland died sunday at phelps memorial hospital in north 
tarrytown of respiratory failure brought on by pneumonia he was 
90 he had recently suffered two strokes 
he created the american sound in symphonic music said 
composer william schuman 
copland believed in the validity of american music that we 
were not inferior to our european cousins schuman said he 
wrote music only an american could have written 
copland was being cremated and the funeral service was private 
said his attorney ellis freedman a public musical tribute is 
planned he said 
copland was known for his plainspoken compositions such as 
appalachian spring rodeo and billy the kid the 
brooklynborn son of jewish immigrants from east europe was 
remembered in death as the prototypical american composer 
he had a uniquely american voice and was able to express in 
his music particularly american sensibilities using substantially 
the language of european serious music said kenneth haas 
managing director of the boston symphony orchestra 
coplands composing career gave the world such popular pieces as 
fanfare for the common man an orchestral composition the late 
leonard bernstein once called the alltime top of the hit parade 
in american music 
copland won the 1944 pulitzer prize for composition for 
appalachian spring which was commissioned by choreographer 
martha graham an oscar for his musical score of the heiress in 
1948 and the presidential medal of freedom in 1964 
graham on retreat in hawaii after completing a sixweek far 
east tour called copland a very dear friend and a very great 
artist 
aaron and i and appalachian spring have had such a long 
journey together she said in a statement released by her 
manhattanbased dance company it is very difficult for me to 
accept that he is gone 
another dance great agnes demille also mourned coplands 
death but outspoken as always demille said she did not think of 
copland as a worldclass composer 
he was a very great composer the finest we had hes not by 
any means in a world class but i liked him awfully she 
said he was wonderful to work with charming to be with an 
expert worker 
demille recalled when copland told her he had started conducting 
and mentioned how much he enjoyed it by the way he was a bad 
conductor she interjected and continued 
he then said agnes have you ever conducted and i said 
of all the damn fool questions you ever asked me aaron that one 
takes the cake 
the anecdote shows the simple side of copland a man who many 
described as a downtoearth uncomplicated genius 
usually geniuses are selfcentered and i thought how can a 
man be a genius and still be so nice recalled pulitzer 
prizewinning composer david del tredici who claims copland as his 
mentor 
copland quit composing in the early 1970s and swore he didnt 
miss it 
youd think if you had spent 50 years at it youd have the 
feeling that something was missing and i really dont he told 
an interviewer 
i must have expressed myself sufficiently i certainly dont 
feel tortured or bitter only lucky to have been given so long to 
be creative and resigned to the fact that it appears to be over 
at his birthday celebration two weeks ago copland ate apple 
pie which he preferred to cake surrounded by longtime friends he 
read messages from young fans 
he was not the least pretentious said schuman if you 
didnt know he was one of the greatest artists of the century you 
would never suspect it 
copland taught at the boston symphonys tanglewood music school 
in lenox mass for 25 years and was head of the faculty there 
when he stepped down in 1970 his students included bernstein and 
composer lukas foss 
he lived a very productive 90 years haas said happily 
we will have his music to appreciate even though we dont have him 
any more 
copland a lifelong bachelor is survived by a niece felice 
marlin of manhattan and two nephews ralph marcus of stuart fla 
and burton marcus of woodmere 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

