<TEXT>
after 15 years of civil war 
marxistinspired oneparty rule foreign invasion and economic 
crisis angolas leaders begin a new strugle on tuesday to 
radically change the nature of their country 
president jose eduardo dos santoss party is to debate plans at 
a congress being held to introduce multiparty democracy and a free 
market economy and to discuss peace terms with the usbacked 
unita guerrilla movement 
in preparing to emulate his allies in the soviet union dos 
santos faces a challenge from hardliners within his popular 
movement for the liberation of angola or mpla they have yet to 
follow him in dropping marxist rhetoric and embracing his new 
option of democratic socialism 
in 11 years as party leader and president of the wartorn 
southern african nation dos santos has survived the jockeying for 
power within the mpla 
he has given strong signals in recent months however that he 
plans to abandon the communist model and open the political system 
to opposition forces including unita the national union for the 
total independence of angola 
jonas savimbis unita rebels have been fighting the mpla since 
angola gaindd independence from portugal in 1975 
the two sides opened peace talks in portugal last april to end 
their war which has devastated what is potentially one of the 
richest countries in africa 
at the fifth round of talks last month portuguese officials 
mediating the negotiations said a ceasefire was in sight 
a truce must be followed by political changes allowing unita a 
stake in angolas future 
this weeks congress is to discuss major constitutional reforms 
aimed at removing the ruling partys position as the guiding force 
in society legalizing opposition groups and preparing for general 
elections 
dos santos says a multiparty system can be implemented early 
next year 
to ensure support for the changes he is expected to remove at 
least five longtime members from the 13member politburo and 
officially shed the partys marxist ideology 
subsaharan africas secondlargaest nation angola is rich in 
oil diamonds and other minerals it has an abundance of arable 
land and wellstocked atlantic fishing grounds its deepwater 
ports at luanda and lobito could be a key economic outlet for other 
southern african nations 
but fighting has crippled economic activity and cut 
communications only exports from the heavily guarded northwestern 
oil fields have kept the economy afloat 
also an estimated 2 million of angolas 10 million people face 
famine after a fouryear drought 
dos santos concedes that war was not the only cause of angolas 
economic woes he admitted in a recent address before 700 
businessmen in luanda that the centralized system adopted by all of 
portugals african colonies after independence resulted in many 
errors 
the most important dos santos said was not understanding the 
role of private enterprise in angolas economic recovery 
he promised reforms that would aid smallbusiness owners and 
encourage foreign investment a longawaited devaluation of the 
kwanza was introduced in september as part of an austerity program 
the government and unita remain divided on such issues as the 
timing of elections integration of the two armed forces and the 
composition of an international force to verify a ceasefire 
while both sides have expressed cautious optimism after last 
months talks fighting has flared since unita commandos conducted 
daring raids on economic targets in the luanda area last week 
blowing up bridges water pipes and electricity lines they damaged 
the luanda oil refinery leaving the capital facing energy and gas 
shortages 
a cuban officer and two soldiers were killed in the attacks 
cuba maintains about 10000 soldiers here from the estimated 
50000 stationed in angola since the late1970s in a 1988 
agreement with south africa which had made incursions into angola 
cuba said it would withdraw its force and south africa pledged to 
halt its aid to unita 
the united states has said it will not stop helping unita until 
the government guarantees the rebels a role in a mulitparty 
society 
</TEXT>
