<TEXT>
the us department of energy said monday 
it is investigating an engineers complaint she was harassed after 
warning that emptying two tanks at the hanford nuclear reservation 
could cause an explosion 
her warning was later vindicated by a general accounting office 
report that said too little was known about the explosive potential 
of the tanks 
engineer inez austin contends employer westinghouse hanford co 
is destroying her career because of her alert 
ken morgan of the department of energys richland office said 
monday that the agency takes harassment of whistleblowers 
seriously we do not have much firsthand information about ms 
austins case he said 
a hanford watchdog group said the incident was the latest in a 
pattern of harassment against whistleblowers on the reservation in 
southcentral washington hanford for decades produced plutonium 
for nuclear weapons but now is largely focusing on cleaning up 
years of contamination at the federal site 
the harassment of whistleblowers who are trying to protect 
the public from extremely dangerous waste tanks is rampant said 
gerald pollet of heart of america northwest 
six weeks ago energy secretary james watkins toured hanford and 
promised whistleblowers would be protected and rewarded last 
month westinghouse hanford issued guidelines for protecting 
whistleblowers 
ms austin who made her concerns public saturday said weve 
always been told if there is a problem go to your manager and if 
there is a safety concern they will listen it is a blow to find 
out it is not true 
last june ms austin contends she demanded a delay in the 
pumping of radioactive liquids from two waste storage tanks that 
the company did not want to grant the pumping was canceled anyway 
after the gao report 
the tanks contained ferrocyanide which could explode if 
internal tank temperatures top 400 degrees fahrenheit the chemical 
was added in the 1950s to concentrate the tank liquids 
ms austin who had served on a panel that analyzed the safety 
of pumping 22 tanks containing ferrocyanide had been asked to 
approve the emptying of two tanks she refused saying that 
removing liquids could cause the internal temperatures to rise 
possibly to dangerous levels said tom carpenter an attorney for 
the private government accountability project 
the next day she argued with her supervisor and another engineer 
over the refusal carpenter said 
westinghouse spokesman john burk said the technology did not 
allow enough of the liquid to be removed from the sludge at the 
bottom of the tank to raise internal temperatures he also said 15 
of the frrocyanide tanks had been pumped in the past without 
incident 
ms austin a westinghouse employee since 1979 contends she has 
since suffered a reduction of duties a poor job evaluation 
failure to receive mail and even constant temperature fluctuations 
in her office she said the actions were designed to make her quit 
which she has not done 
she said she has filed a complaint with the us department of 
labor 
after the argument ms austin took the rest of the day and the 
next day as vacation days carpenter said burk said westinghouse 
employees are not allowed to take vacation days on such short 
notice 
her manager gave her a letter of reprimand said burk 
adding that the company has since rescinded the letter he said 
westinghouse hanford president roger nichols is personally 
investigating some of her allegations 
</TEXT>
