<TEXT>
the bush administration monday predicted in a 
report to congress that the us trade deficit would remain steady 
even though americans are paying sharply more for imported oil 
prepared by the treasury department as a requirement of the 1988 
trade law the report also indicated that a further decline in the 
value of the dollar was not needed to improve the nations trade 
balance 
it predicted a sustaining of the progress made in reducing 
the current account deficit which is the broadest measure of trade 
and includes investment flows 
the deficit has dropped from a peak of 162 billion in 1987 to 
129 billion in 1988 and 110 billion in 1989 during the first six 
months of 1990 it ran at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 87 
billion 
the us deficit and japanese and german surpluses are being 
further reduced this year despite repeated prognostications that 
the external adjustment process had come to a halt and that 
balances would resume widening the report said 
international monetary fund forecast indicate the us deficit 
will remain below 100 billion next year despite the runup in oil 
prices the report said however it noted that the standoff in the 
persian gulf between the united states and iraq made predictions 
more uncertain than usual 
i dont view that as tremendous news said economist robert 
g dederick of northern trust co in chicago a number that is 
stalling out at around 100 billion is still a problem 
moreover he and other economists said the prediction likely 
would prove true only if the price of oil falls next year and if 
economy topples into a recession as many analysts believe is 
happening 
my guess is the treasury department is right for the wrong 
reasons said economist michael k evans who heads a washington 
consulting firm trade deficits always narrow in a recession 
because people buy fewer imports 
the reports stance on the dollar reflects a shift in the 
thinking of administration officials who as recently as two months 
ago expressed little concern with the currencys decline so long as 
it was orderly 
a lower dollar helps the us trade deficit by making american 
goods cheaper abroad and foreign goods more expensive in the united 
states 
however a falling dollar encourages inflation in the united 
states by reducing americans spending power it also tends to push 
up the interest rate foreign investors demand to finance the us 
budget deficit 
when the treasury last issued its trade report in april 
officials were concerned about the advance of the dollar against 
the japanese yen but since then the dollar has fallen 18 percent 
against the yen and is trading near postworld war ii lows against 
the german mark 
the report said further adjustment of external imbalances 
should rely primarily on macroeconomic and structural policy 
measures rather than on further exchange rate adjustment 
macroeconomic and structural policy measures is a reference 
to us efforts to cut its budget deficit reducing the need for 
foreign funds and german and japanese efforts to stimulate 
consumer demand for us goods 
evans and dederick said the administrations shift toward 
supporting the dollar was made to counteract foreign disappointment 
with the fiveyear budget deficit reduction pact enacted at the end 
of october 
the report said the deficit reduction pact demonstrates the 
united states commitment to putting its economic house in order 
but dederick said this is not viewed abroad as very 
meaningful 
