<TEXT>
farmers in the russian republic may own land for 
the first time in more than 60 years but must wait a decade to sell 
it under a measure passed monday by the russian parliament 
farmers will be free now they will be free in choosing the 
ways and methods of their work and property russian president 
boris n yeltsin told a news conference after what he called an 
historic vote 
yeltsin said farmers told him that allowing private ownership 
would boost production in a year or two 
this winter however the soviet union must rely in part on food 
purchased or donated abroad 
after four days of acrimonious debate a hush fell over the 
russian congress of peoples deputies as lawmakers voted 86390 
with 40 abstentions to reverse a land policy in effect since 
dictator josef stalin carried out a bloody collectivization of land 
between 1929 and 1932 millions died in the resulting famine and 
soviet agriculture took decades to regain earlier production 
levels 
legislators cheered when the bill passed and yeltsin said later 
that euphoria is natural when people have waited so long 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev has recommended a 
nationwide referendum on reversing collectivization but yeltsin 
said the solid majority in the russian parliament showed wide 
backing for the move 
many opponents of the measure doubt whether farmers would buy 
land they say that even before collectivization many small 
landholders in the russian republic worked under a communal system 
of land ownership private land ownership by small landholders was 
more common in other republics 
the national legislature has yet to approve the sale of 
farmland it was not clear whether passage of the measure by the 
parliament of the russian federation by far the largest of the 15 
soviet republics would force the kremlins hand or spark a 
constitutional battle 
the three baltic republics which declared independence earlier 
this year have also passed laws allowing private land ownership 
although the process is bogged down in disputes over property 
rights 
the newly elected noncommunist parliament of georgia is 
expected to pass a law soon allowing private farmland 
yeltsin said the measure passed monday will revive hundreds of 
thousands of russian villages that are being abandoned by farmers 
who find it impossible to earn a decent living on stateowned land 
selling at stateset prices to a state distribution system 
although private holdings will be allowed he said collective 
farm and other types of ownership will remain in existence 
competing for their place in the market all forms of ownership are 
equal and protected by law 
under the terms of the fourpoint resolution the russian 
legislature will enact laws specifying how to break up collective 
farms local legislative councils will have the final say on 
whether to decollectivize 
the resale of land would be blocked for 10 years and then it 
could be sold back only to the state 
parliament may decide to allow outright sale of land before 
the 10 years are over if we see that these processes are going 
smoothly yeltsin said 
russian farmers he said are set against buying or selling 
land because they are afraid land will be an object of 
speculation 
the original proposal would have allowed the resale of land 
after five years 
russian peasants are not used to selling land the land which 
is called mother said yeltsin some lawmakers have been saying 
that a mother is not for sale 
yeltsin also stressed the need to monitor shipments of foreign 
food into the soviet union over the next three or four months 
in this mess the mafia can make great use of this and 
sell it on the side he said 
soviet crop yields were high this year but much was lost due to 
poor transportation and storage facilities 
