<TEXT>
even if the baltic republics refuse to sign a new 
union treaty they will remain part of the soviet union unless they 
follow constitutional procedures for secession a top soviet 
legislator said monday 
rafik nishanov chairman of the council of nationalities one of 
two chambers in the supreme soviet legislature issued the warning 
to the baltics as he formally submitted the treaty to lawmakers 
another challenge to the treaty came from russian president 
boris yeltsin who said the giant republic would not sign until 
soviet president mikhail gorbachev recognizes the republics right 
to control its own economy 
gorbachev has been pushing hard for adoption of the treaty to 
hold the 15 soviet republics together 
it would replace the 1922 document that formally created the 
soviet union and would give the restive republics more economic and 
political autonomy but a strong central government in moscow would 
retain control over defense foreign policy taxation monetary 
policy electric power and transportation 
nishanovs speech indicated that the gorbachev government is 
maintaining a hard line on the issue of secession 
gorbachev sat on the rostrum during the legislative session but 
did not speak 
