<TEXT>
the earthquake that rocked the los angeles 
basin and caused 12 million in damage in february may only be the 
prelude to a nastier jolt to come scientists said monday 
the upland earthquake feb 28 which measured 52 on the richter 
scale failed to relieve stress on the san jose fault said egill 
hauksson a seismologist at the california institute of technology 
in pasadena 
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy an earthquake 
releases as measured by the ground motion recorded on a 
seismograph 
as a result of that unspent stress the san jose fault may 
produce a quake measuring 6 to 65 on the richter scale hauksson 
said during the american geophysical unions fall meeting 
scientists couldnt say when that might be he said 
the last quake of that size in the los angeles basin was the 
feb 9 1971 san fernandosylmar quake which had a magnitude of 
64 it killed 65 people and injured 2000 more as it collapsed 
freeway overpasses and caused 511 million in damage 
the new study of the san jose faults potential for disaster was 
conducted by hauksson and his wife us geological survey 
seismologist lucy jones 
roughly 11 miles long the san jose fault starts near the base 
of the san gabriel mountains north of upland and runs southwest 
near claremont and pomona 
the feb 28 quake was centered 3 miles northwest of upland a 
community 40 miles east of downtown los angeles it shook much of 
the los angeles basin causing minor injuries and 118 million in 
damage 
the quake ruptured the faults northeastern 2 miles 
the other 8mile section hasnt broken in any recent 
earthquake hauksson said he and jones analyzed the type of 
faulting caused by the aftershocks in a quake in 1988 and the one 
in february 
they concluded the two quakes failed to relieve stress on the 
rest of the san jose fault which by its length could produce a 
jolt of 6 to 65 magnitude 
there are still forces stored up in the region that could 
produce another earthquake as large or larger than what weve 
already had jones said 
but far worse has been projected for southern california the 
socalled big one on the san andreas fault that scientists say 
will measure 75 to 8 or more in magnitude 
a 1988 geological survey report said such an event quake is at 
least 60 percent likely by the year 2018 an earlier federal report 
said it could kill up to 14000 people hospitalize 55000 and 
cause 17 billion in damage 
but scientists believe the region will be shaken more often by 
smaller but still deadly quakes on other faults including the san 
jacinto fault the elysian park fault and the newportinglewood 
fault 
</TEXT>
