<TEXT>
the exotic calypsoflavored world of a papa 
doclike haiti is a far cry from a grim world ii soviet union but 
the caucasian chalk circle survives the transplant with most of 
its theatricality intact 
director george c wolfe has done an impressive job in moving 
bertolt brechts political parable into a magical mystical 
caribbean wonderland where violence and a childlike innocence 
exist side by side this revival which opened offbroadway last 
weekend at the new york shakespeare festival public theater 
reverberates with a sense of style and place that rarely betrays 
the material 
wolfe uses song dance outlandish costumes masks and puppets 
to tell brechts story of a kitchen maid who rescues the child of a 
deposed political leader and flees with the baby to safety after 
the revolution the biological mother wants her son back and the 
case goes before a peasantturnedjudge for resolution 
chalk circle has been transformed by thulani davis who 
skillfully adapted an englishlanguage version of the play moving 
the locale from the caucasus in 1945 to presentday haiti 
a long first act which actually cuts brechts cumbersome 
prologue captures the works fairytale quality several actors 
are of enormous help in telling the story particularly novella 
nelson as the strongvoiced narrator and charlayne woodard as the 
courageous maid who risks all for the baby in her fight for the 
child woodard displays a conviction that blends equal amounts of 
charm and determination altogether beguiling 
the show and the showmanship falter in a meandering act 2 when 
the parable shifts into political tract the humor becomes 
heavyhanded primarily because actor reggie montgomery who plays 
the judge mugs his way through the role montgomery manages to 
shrink what should be a star turn into a performance of sitcom 
size 
but it doesnt fatally damage the evening there are still those 
other distinctive performances to watch as well as the colorful 
costumes by tonileslie james and the mask and puppet designs by 
barbara pollitt and stephen kaplin 
wolfe has had other successes at the public including his own 
funny fractured revue of black life called the colored museum 
and spunk an adaptation of three short stories by zora neale 
hurston 
with the caucasian chalk circle hes shown he can take a 
masterpiece and turn it inside out and into something provocatively 
different 
