<TEXT>
a federal judge on monday cleared the way for a 
retrial of former congressman robert garcia on charges he extorted 
payments from the scandalplagued wedtech corp 
us district judge leonard b sand denied a double jeopardy 
motion that claimed garcia a bronx democrat and his wife jane 
could not be tried twice for the same offense after an appeals 
court reversed their october 1989 convictions 
one might argue that a defendant should be required to run the 
gauntlet of the criminal process only once and that if a conviction 
fails for any reason to pass appellate muster the defendant must 
go free sand wrote in his opinion 
but the supreme court of the united states has clearly 
established the law is otherwise 
ronald fischetti the lawyer representing mrs garcia said they 
had not decided whether to appeal sands ruling garcias attorney 
robert morvillo was unavailable for comment his office said 
their new trial was scheduled to begin jan 21 
a threejudge panel of the 2nd us circuit court of appeals 
reversed the couples convictions in june on grounds there was 
insufficient evidence to prove one of two prosecution theories 
supporting the extortion charge 
the appeals court ruled that since the jurors did not specify 
which theory they adopted the garcias should be retried 
under sands ruling the new trial will focus on the theory that 
the garcias used the congressmans political office to obtain 
payoffs from wedtech a bronxbased military contractor that 
collapsed in 1986 in the midst of a corruption scandal 
the appeals court rejected the theory that garcia and his wife 
intimidated wedtech officers into making the payments 
the indictment accuses the garcias of extorting monthly payments 
totaling 76000 and obtaining a 20000 interestfree loan from 
wedtech in 1984 in return for future favors 
garcia 58 resigned his seat in congress in january after he 
and his wife were sentenced by sand to three years in prison with 
the recommendation they be released on parole after six months 
he began serving his sentence in march but was released in june 
after the appellate courts decision 
other politicians convicted in the wedtech scandal were former 
us rep mario biaggi and a former bronx borough president 
stanley simon 
