railroad stops after the metropolitan transportation authority 
canceled permits 
the transportation agency said it acted because of concerns that 
strikers would set up picket lines that would be honored by transit 
workers creating a work slowdown that might halt operations 
on dec 3 first day of the transit sales there were no reports 
of problems with daily news hawkers at subway stations transit 
officials had no count of how many hawkers were selling at 60 
approved sites around the city but caren gardner of the ta said 
there doesnt appear to be many out there 
the newspapers civil lawsuit against the unions was filed in 
us district court in manhattan on nov 29 and alleges violations 
of the racketeer influenced corrupt organizations act or rico the 
suit claims that a conspiracy exists involving attempted murder 
coercion arson and robbery named are the newspaper and mail 
deliverers union of new york and vicinity the allied printing 
trades council the umbrella group representing the nine striking 
unions and 23 drivers some of whom have been arrested during the 
strike 
the lawsuit claims the groups want to force the paper to accept 
a settlement that contains abuses the news has tried to end in 10 
months of negotiations 
the news also claimed that through violence the unions hoped to 
implement a buyout plan organized by theodore kheel the unions 
unpaid legal adviser kheel is not being sued 
a 6inch pipe bomb was found dec 2 near a parking area at the 
companys brooklyn printing plant police said nearby were two 
unexploded m80 firecrackers taped to boxes of nails 
police had gone there to investigate 12 explosions apparently 
caused by firecrackers sgt peter sweeney a police spokesman 
said one man was arrested for throwing a bottle that hit an 
officer four demonstrators were also arrested for disorderly 
conduct 
in separate incidents the same day police said two news 
replacement drivers were charged with weapons possession after a 
loaded 25caliber handgun was found in the front seat of their 
truck and a striking pressman was charged in the assault of a 
daily news hawker 
the strike by about 2100 workers began oct 25 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
rupert murdochs news corp says it hopes to 
reach an agreement with bankers by early january on a new financing 
plan that would defer repayment on about 5 billion in debt for the 
next three years 
the australianbased company has amassed a large debt by 
aggressively expanding into newspapers book publishing movie and 
tv production television stations and magazines 
but unexpectedly slow assets sales economic weakness in britain 
and australia and a sluggish advertising market in the united 
states have made it tough to keep up with debt payments 
murdoch has met over the past few weeks with groups of bankers 
in australia europe and the united states to outline a proposal to 
consolidate about 65 billion in bank loans otherwise due by 
mid1993 
an executive source close to the news corp chief executive but 
speaking on condition of anonymity said nov 29 that murdoch made 
the proposal because principal payments are coming due that the 
company would have trouble paying 
under terms of the proposed package only 14 billion in bank 
loans would have to be repaid by december 1993 the executive said 
the company would then hope to renegotiate the remainder by early 
1994 he said 
in exchange for permitting the debt deferral the bankers would 
get higher rates of interest and other fees the company has also 
told the bankers it plans to sell about 1 billion in assets over 
the next two years 
as part of the refinancing proposal news corp would get a 600 
million bridge loan that would have to be repaid in mid1992 the 
bridge loan would give the company the ability to make interest 
payments meet business expenses and allow extra time to arrange 
asset sales 
news corp purchased the book publisher harper amp row 20th 
century fox film corp several television stations and triangle 
publications the owner of tv guide and the daily racing form in 
the past few years 
under its existing loan agreemnt news corp would have had to 
pay back 24 billion in both bank loans and public debt by next 
june another 14 billion by june 1992 and 3 billion by june 
1993 
the new agreement would require no repayments by next june 12 
billion including the bridge loan by june 1992 and another 800 
million by june 1993 with the chance for delaying the final payment 
until december 1993 
</TEXT>
