<TEXT>
glen renfrew who guided reuters through a decade 
of strong profit growth will step down as chief executive in 
march the company announced nov 29 
he will be replaced by peter job a 49yearold reuters veteran 
who started as a journalist before moving up the management ladder 
to his current post as managing director for reuters in asia 
the announcement comes during a bumpy but still profitable year 
for reuters which renfrew said included a high number of 
cancellations of the companys financial services 
earlier in november the company said it would cut 300 jobs from 
its work force of 10500 and delay the launch of a new automatic 
foreign exchange dealing system because of unsettled market 
conditions 
reuters chairman sir christopher hogg told a news conference 
that renfrews departure had nothing to do with the companys 
performance this year the agency said it still would have record 
pretax profits of about 627 million even after absorbing 
severance pay worth 196 million 
hogg said renfrew 62 had informed the board 15 months ago of 
his decision to retire after a successor had been picked 
the whole process has been a planned one said hogg who 
paid tribute to renfrew for leading reuters through a period of 
quite outstanding growth and prosperity as chief executive and 
managing director 
hogg said renfrew had already stayed two years beyond the normal 
pensionable age for senior reuters executives mandatory retirement 
is at 65 
neil blackley a media analyst at the brokerage james capel and 
co also said it would be wrong to link reuters recent 
difficulties with renfrews leaving next march 
he had a decade of meteoric profit growth but the last nine 
months have been difficult blackley said its a shame he has 
to end on that note 
blackley said he was pleased with the appointment of job whom 
he described as very talented 
job a graduate of oxford university served as a foreign 
correspondent and news executive in india malaysia indonesia 
britain and latin america before moving into business management in 
1974 he has been head of reuters asia since 1988 
renfrew an australian joined reuters in london in 1952 after 
graduating from sydney university he was in charge of reuters 
north american operations from 1971 until his promotion to chief 
executive in 1981 
when he took over as ceo reuters was owned by a publishers 
association representing newspapers in britian ireland australia 
and new zealand it had 2700 employees then 
renfrew guided reuters through a complicated transformation into 
a public company reuters holdings plc in 1984 in the past five 
years pretax profits have risen steadily with each year setting a 
new record 
renfrew sold 20 percent of his personal holdings in the company 
last august for about 337 million that left him with 849378 
shares worth 1055 million the day his departure was announced 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
financial news network inc said nov 29 it 
expects to report a 725 million loss for fiscal 1990 
the company whose biggest shareholder is the owner of the 
united press international wire service also said it expects to 
report a loss of 25 million for the first quarter of its current 
fiscal year 
the company has been unable to report its financial results for 
the fiscal year ended june 30 because it replaced its auditing firm 
in a controversy over how fnn was reporting a 28 million 
investment in a new service 
the auditors deloitte amp touche contended the investment should 
have been deducted from quarterly earnings while fnn wanted to 
spread the costs over a few years 
deloitte left as fnns auditor in october and the firm coopers amp 
lybrand was brought in to study the fnn annual financial 
statements 
fnn said that its new auditors had substantially completed 
their examination and said it expects to file its audited 
financial statements with the securities and exchange commission in 
early december 
fnn said the anticipated net loss for he year would leave it 
with a shareholders deficit of approximately 335 million at 
june 30 
the shareholders deficit represents an excess of liabilities 
over assets 
the company said it would probably file amended quarterly 
reports for the first nine months of fiscal 1990 to reflect 
material changes deemed appropriate as a result of the audit 
in addition it said it expects to report within a few weeks a 
25 million loss for the first fiscal quarter ended sept 30 
fnn said that more than half of the anticipated losses for the 
year and the first quarter involves elimination of revenues derived 
from affiliated businesses 
the company did not identify the affiliates but it is 46 
percent owned by infotechnology inc which owns upi and an 
assortment of other media and technology companies 
it was disclosed last month that the sec is investigating 
infotechnology for undisclosed reasons infotechnology and fnn have 
each said they do not have enough cash flow to cover operating 
expenses and are negotiating with those to whom they owe money 
in late october alan j hirschfield and allan r tessler were 
brought in to succeed earl brian as interim cochief executives at 
both infotechnology and financial news network 
in early november they said they were putting the companies 
principal operations up for sale including the fnn cable network 
and upi 
in the nov 29 announcement hirschfield and tessler said fnns 
investment banker wertheim amp schroder amp co inc is beginning the 
sale process for fnn 
a substantial number of inquires have been received from a 
broad representation of mediarelated companies and others 
concerning the proposed sale of fnn the statement said 
infotechnology spokeswoman amber gordon said she could not 
identify who was interested or how many inquiries had been 
received she said the company hopes to conclude negotiations of 
the contracts for the sales by the end of the year 
fnn provides stock quotes business and financial news and 
sports information on a cable tv network to more than 35 million 
homes served by 3500 cable systems in the united states and 
canada 
it also operates a business radio network and with 
infotechnology owns 51 percent of the learning channel cable 
network 
