<TEXT>
executives from the recordjournal of 
meriden the hartford courant and the new haven register said they 
plan to fight on constitutional grounds a directive that bans news 
racks from city sidewalks 
city officials began notifying area newspapers nov 29 that the 
vending machines had to be removed from sidewalks and certain other 
locations 
a onesentence section of a local zoning ordinance prohibits 
placement of vending machines between a city street and a property 
line effectively banning them from city sidewalks it also 
requires machines on private property to be a certain distance from 
the street although that distance varies depending on the areas 
zone designation 
but newspaper officials said numerous court cases including a 
1988 us supreme court decision have upheld newspapers first 
amendment right to maintain the machines 
a letter mailed to the three newspapers said their machines have 
to be removed within 30 days if they are not ceaseanddesist 
orders will be issued and the city will begin enforcement actions 
city planner dominick j caruso said he said the same letter will 
go out to other newspapers that own vending machines in the city 
but city manager michael h aldi later said he believes the 
ordinance may be unconstitutional and that intends to seek a legal 
opinion to resolve the issue 
caruso said the regulation has been on the books for a long 
time its just never been brought up before caruso said he was 
unaware of the law until recently when he received a complaint 
eliot c white publisher of the recordjournal and president of 
the recordjournal publishing co said the matter revolves around 
an outofdate ordinance thats never been enforced as far as we 
know 
the recordjournal maintains 50 vending machines in the city 
in a 1988 case the supreme court ruled that a lakewood ohio 
official could not prevent a cleveland newspaper from putting out 
news racks by denying them a permit to do so according to alice 
neff lucan a washington dc attorney who has handled similar 
cases 
it is extremely unlikely in my opinion that just by coloring 
this a vending machine issue they can prevent newspapers from 
distributing said neff lucan who represents usa today which 
owns machines in the city the distribution and publication of 
newspapers is protected by the free speech provisions of the first 
amendment she said 
william j rush chief executive officer of the new haven 
register said he has seen municipalities try to outlaw news racks 
its always boiled down to our constitutional rights under the 
first amendment he said we try to be good citizens but we 
intend to keep our boxes on the street and we intend to protect our 
constitutional rights 
the register has about 35 machines in meriden 
raymond a jansen publisher of the hartford courant said his 
paper has encountered this a number of times over the years and 
we typically try to work with city officials to position the 
machines where theyd like to see them 
but if it comes down to not allowing them wed view that very 
seriously jansen said we would seek legal advice as to how 
the law could be enforced in the face of the first amendment 
</TEXT>
