the kentucky supreme court has upheld a 
libel judgment against the kentucky post won by a prosecutor who 
claimed the newspaper defamed him 
the court in a unanimous ruling nov 29 also upheld the 
175000 jury award to campbell commonwealths attorney louis a 
ball for compensatory damages from the newspaper reporter al 
salvato and the ew scripps co which owns the post no punitive 
damages were awarded 
the newspaper published frontpage stories on nov 17 and 19 
1984 titled portrait of a prosecutor outlining what the paper 
said was balls poor record as prosecutor 
included was a comment from a former narcotics officer who said 
criminals couldnt have a better friend than ball 
the courts ruling said there was ample evidence the newspaper 
printed erroneous material that it knew was wrong or made 
insufficient effort to determine if it was wrong 
the circumstances surrounding the newspapers reporting and 
publishing of the story all led to the conclusion the articles were 
printed maliciously the court said 
we include in the circumstances surrounding publication the 
way in which the articles were laid out the evidence regarding 
malice and the failure to make any retraction justice 
charles leibson said in the opinion 
kentucky post editor judith clabes called the ruling gravely 
disappointing 
its an unbecoming decision from a political body that has 
demonstrated in a number of instances that when it comes to the 
press politics and emotions are more controlling than the law 
she said 
the court completely ignored the facts of the case and 
misrepresented the facts of the case clabes said 
