<TEXT>
new yorks top court ruled nov 27 that 
regents disciplinary hearings involving doctors and other 
professionals should be closed to the public unless those accused 
of misconduct want them open 
the court of appeals ruled unanimously against the johnson 
newspaper corp publisher of the watertown daily times which had 
argued that hearings conducted by the state board of regents should 
be open 
the state board of regents is responsible for disciplining 32 
licensed professions including doctors nurses architects and 
veteranarians traditionally the regents have kept their 
misconduct cases against professionals confidential until they 
decide a persons guilt or innocence said christopher carpenter 
state education department spokesman 
the daily times in april 1988 sought access to a disciplinary 
hearing involving a watertown dentist that hearing has been held 
up pending determination of this case 
the court of appeals said nothing in state law or tradition 
supports opening the hearings to the public 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the states open records law would be 
meaningless if it did not apply to a university of south carolina 
foundation that has received and spent public money two news 
organizations told the state supreme court nov 27 
the decision of this court will determine whether this 
powerful law is really meaningful or whether this is a makebelieve 
world of form over substance said wallace lightsey attorney for 
the associated press and the greenville news 
the carolina research and development foundation has appealed a 
lower court order to make the records public 
circuit judge carol connor ruled in june 1989 that the 
foundation was subject to the freedom of information act because it 
accepted and spent about 28 million in public money her order was 
set aside pending the outcome of the foundations appeal to the 
supreme court 
foundation attorney hoover blanton said the foi law should not 
apply to a private group unless a large amount of the groups 
budget came from public money 
attorneys did not expect a ruling until next year 
</TEXT>
