the supreme court on nov 26 refused to kill 
two fairhousing lawsuits stemming from newspaper real estate 
advertisements showing only white models posing as homeowners 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that forces 
developers of a virginia condominium community to defend themselves 
in a jury trial against allegations they violated federal law 
the suits center on ads that appeared in the washington post 
over a 17month period beginning in 1985 for colonial village a 
condo community in arlington just across the potomac river from 
the district of columbia 
the suits were filed by girardeau spann a black resident of 
washington who is a professor at georgetown universitys law 
school and two advocacy groups the metropolitan washington 
planning and housing association and the fair housing council of 
greater washington 
named as defendants are colonial village inc and its parent 
firm mobil land development corp a subsidiary of the oil 
company 
the lawsuits allege that the defendants violated the fair 
housing act by featuring only white models in ads that appeared in 
the post the suits said the ads were racially preferential and 
discriminatory and they sought an injunction and monetary damages 
a federal trial judge in 1987 threw out the suits ruling they 
had been filed too late 
but the us circuit court of appeals here reinstated them last 
march 13 and sent the dispute back to us district judge harold 
greene for trial 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the pulitzer prize board said nov 26 it has 
renamed and redefined two journalism categories 
the category that had been general news reporting has been 
renamed spot news reporting and will be given for local reporting 
of spot news it was formerly given for local reporting of spot 
news or consistent beat coverage 
the category that had been specialized reporting has been 
renamed beat reporting its former definition was for reporting 
on such specialized subjects as sports business science 
education or religion 
now the category will cover any form of consistent 
specialized reporting from police beat coverage to religion 
writing said robert c christopher board secretary and prize 
administrator 
the boards intention was to give these two category 
definitions greater clarity and simplicity and eliminate any 
appearance of overlap between them christopher said in a 
statement 
the deadline is feb 1 for submitting articles photographs and 
cartoons published in daily or weekly us newspapers during 1990 
the winners will be announced april 9 1991 
the other journalism categories are public service 
investigative reporting explanatory journalism national 
reporting international reporting feature writing commentary 
criticism editorial writing editorial cartooning spot news 
photography and feature photography 
</TEXT>
