the sunday correspondent a nationally distributed 
weekly newspaper launched last year has closed after failing to 
meet circulation targets 
the newspaper was started at a cost of 255 million and 
included the chicago tribune among its shareholders 
sales of the paper fell below the 350000 figure needed to break 
even and last august shareholders pumped in another 19 million to 
keep it going the papers chief executive nick shott said nov 
27 that its final circulation had fallen to 210000 
the closing leaves britain with 10 national weekly sunday 
newspapers 
like its competitors and tv and radio stations the paper has 
been hit by falling advertising revenue in britains current 
economic recession 
shott said the closing will mean the loss of about 200 jobs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
cbs inc is considering a share repurchase 
program following the disclosure that it expects a fourthquarter 
loss and lower earnings next year a published report said 
the media companys stock fell after the nov 19 earnings 
forecast although it gained ground later along with other media 
stocks 
the wall street journal said nov 29 that people familiar with 
the proposal said cbs is considering a socalled dutch auction as 
one share buyback option 
in a dutch auction a company states the number of shares it 
wants to buy in a specified period and gives a price range within 
which shareholders may tender their shares the company then 
selects a price in the range that will enable it to buy all the 
shares it needs 
that might enable cbs to buy back part or all of the 8 percent 
stake held by the estate of the late cbs founder william s paley 
paleys shares are to be divided among his six children but may 
have to be sold to cover tax obligations 
cbs had no immediate comment on the report 
in the earnings forecast cbs said it expected to post a loss in 
the fourth quarter compared with earnings of about 60 million in 
the same period a year ago because of losses at its cbs television 
network 
cbs has only posted one other quarterly loss from continuing 
operations in its history and that was 20 million in the fourth 
quarter of 1986 
the company also said it expects its earnings from continuing 
operations in 1991 will be down from this year because of a weak ad 
climate and rising costs for entertainment programs and sports 
rights 
