we keep irreplaceable objects the objectors have an emotional 
response that does not understand that a museum has to be 
accessible to people sellars said 
robert barnard a bronte society member complains that the 
addition would dwarf the parsonage and make it a minor component 
in a bronte theme park 
and secondly the style of the building is hideously out of 
tune with a late georgian house i call it neonorman fortress 
style with its little round windows that look like youre going to 
pour boiling oil out of them barnard said in an interview 
opponents say the extension will cut off the parsonage from the 
starkly beautiful yorkshire moors where the sisters found 
inspiration on walks over the stubbly heather in their long narrow 
shoes 
sellars said the extension would improve the flow of visitors 
through the house and provide better control of the temperature 
and humidity 
traffic clogs to a halt and some furniture is getting brushed 
against which should really be screened off she said 
barnard says the extension is no answer to the problem of wear 
and tear inside the parsonage you still have the same number of 
rooms he said 
the architects plans for the 25 million extension would not 
change the frontal view of the parsonage there would be space for 
an enlarged bronte family history exhibition a meeting room and an 
area for scholars 
sellars said the more than 200 bronte scholars who come each 
year to study the primary sources and manuscripts have to work 
inside the museums small library alongside the societys two 
librarians and their computers and telephones 
the bronte society is a literary society that should be a 
learned society she said the visitors are just shunted 
through the house and then moved on we should be teaching more 
about the literature and the place 
the extension if approved by the bradford county council would 
be built of grit stone and in the vernacular style of the village 
its not like were going to put up a steelmass skyscraper 
sellars said 
opponents have suggested building an addition some distance from 
the parsonage which became a museum in 1928 or even underground 
bronte enthusiasts can take a bit of bad weather we can walk 
outside to get to our meeting room barnard said 
michael steed chairman of the 3240member bronte society said 
the underground addition had not been considered i find it hard 
to believe that visitors coming to haworth would find going into an 
underground museum at all attractive 
barnard said the publicityshy brontes who wrote under 
pseudonyms would have loathed the row over the parsonage indeed 
they would have hated the whole business of people tromping 
through their house because in charlottes time they did come to 
haworth and gawk at where the author of jane eyre lived 
charlotte wrote three other novels and left a fourth unfinished 
born in 1816 she died in 1855 is buried in the church opposite the 
parsonage beside emily 18181848 who wrote wuthering 
heights 
anne 18201849 author of agnes grey and the tenant of 
wildfell hall is buried far away in the coastal town of 
scarborough where she died 
