editors note for the past year since the fall of the berlin 
wall tourists have been rediscovering an older more traditional 
europe to the east a reporter who recently took a cruise on the 
black sea from bulgaria to the soviet crimea found a certain charm 
amid the chaos of a changing economy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
theres a small hotel in fact there 
are hundreds of them that only a year ago were private villas and 
holiday retreats for communist commissars privileged artists and 
favored trade union leaders 
now the vacancy sign is out for tourists from the west or the 
far east since the yen is as welcome as the dollar the pound and 
the mark but please no levs the locals disdain the local 
currency 
and the highrise communist party house as much a fixture in 
every bulgarian city and town as the hulking statue of lenin now 
has offices to rent to shipping firms travel agents exporters and 
all kinds of entrepreneurs pouring into eastern europe since the 
fall of the berlin wall 
this is no longer a communist country we are a developing 
democracy says dmitri our guide from balkantourist the state 
travel agency as he leads a band of tourists off a cruise ship 
through the ruins of roman baths in the second century varna 
then called odessos was a rest center for the roman emperors 
legionnaires 
a little later he leads us up a precarious trail to a 
cliffhanging medieval monastery called aladja 
suddenly last summer all over eastern europe monasteries and 
churches and palaces that had been held in ideological scorn for 
half a century came back in favor those that had been used to 
store grain or billet troops or had been converted to museums of 
atheism were being swept out and refurbished 
and in beach resorts all along the black sea coast from 
bulgarias turkish border to the soviet crimea dreary highrise 
hotels in stolid stalinist gothic are scheduled for 
privatization 
ibusz the hungarian state tourist agency is on the block to 
raise capital to launch capitalism dresden is trying to unload 
from its main square a 22foothigh head of karl marx but so far 
has found no takers 
german golfer bernhard langer the 1985 masters champion is 
prospecting for future course layouts in hungary czechoslovakia 
and what was east germany the royal and ancient game banned for 
decades in communist climes already is in full backswing on an 
island 21 miles up the danube from budapest at a 9hole course 
named szentendre st andrews 
here in varna dmitri says we already have a german beer 
garden an english pub a greek taverna and an indian restaurant 
we think many tourists will be coming our climate is much milder 
than the french riviera you can swim until midoctober 
on a balmy fall day several bathers were slithering down water 
slides and landing splat in mud baths along the wide beach called 
zlatri piassatsi golden sands 
hoping to match neighboring romanias oil finds drillers gushed 
up only mineral springs here some austrian tourists happened by 
after world war ii and insisted the waters cured rheumatism and 
baldness a spa was born 
shepherding his flock into a shopping arcade where some lace 
embroidery and leathercraft were displayed dmitri expresses the 
hope that bulgarias younger generation will hang in there his 
newest english idiom long enough to reap the rewards of a 
freemarket economy 
more than 100000 left the country last year he says a 
million more may go next year 
outside a young man was peddling rare icons that stained 
his jacket with their fresh coat of gilt 
in a square near the ethnographic museum the proprietor of a 
little van advertising beer herring and brandy gave a sadder 
picture of the inflated local currency he had no beer and no 
herring but a plastic cup of slivova strong plum brandy netted 
you change from a onelev note valued at 14 cents 
arriving at yalta in the crimea the cruise passengers wondered 
about the future of the 80 health resorts and sanitaria operated by 
various trade unions and government agencies nestled in the pine 
forests on the bluffs were villas and dachas of toplevel 
commissars and apparatchniki 
our intourist guide worried a little about privatization since 
individual soviet republics now have been given control of their 
own tourism but she doubts that foreign visitors will ever take 
over what she called the comrades coney island last year she 
said 2 million vacationers came to yalta adding that our local 
joke is that they sunbathe standing up 
she was eloquent on yaltas healthgiving climate winds off 
the crimean mountains filtering through the pine forests mingle 
with the black sea breezes to produce an atmosphere that has been 
scientifically proven to be beneficial in the treatment of stress 
rheumatism asthma and cardiovascular ailments 
russian playwright and shortstory writer anton chekhov came for 
treatment of the tuberculosis he aggravated walking all night in 
the snowy streets of moscow in despair over poor notices for the 
seagull leo tolstoy convalesced in a nursing home up on the 
bluffs and was read to under the pines by novelist maxim gorky 
</TEXT>
