<TEXT>
one of the delights of traveling east of vienna austria is 
encountering the older traditional europe 
for the most part the cities are safe after dark the ivers 
are all polluted but the countryside remains unscarred by the 
bulldozer and commercial development muledrawn plows are common 
the pace of life is slower in a society of guaranteed 
employment and subsidized housing health care and even holidays 
there was no rat race 
a year ago any contact with foreigners was forbidden now people 
are eager to practice their rusty english 
but there is a drabness and a sadness about the people they 
betray a sense of having been left behind of having missed out on 
something in the halfcentury of totalitarian rule 
the tourist must not get carried away with the nostalgia 
promised in the new travel brochures old world charm can mean 
the bathroom is a long way down the hall unspoiled can 
translate to never fixed 
telephones dont work toilets dont work in many hotels 
neither do the staffers a system that subsidized idleness and 
inefficiency does not convert readily to the concept of 
customerfriendly 
travelers who have ventured eastward have tales to tell of rats 
in closets beds with fleas restaurants where you bring your own 
bread and the plat du jour is a stew festering with the viscera of 
an unidentified animal and best you dont ask 
