<TEXT>
 
editors note their names are olivier and redgrave and cusack 
three of the most famous names in the london theater this season 
several members of those families are teaming up in the same plays 
a sort of thinking mans osmonds as one newspaper columnist 
put it 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
despite some sniping that it smacks of gimmickry 
the london theater is celebrating its english and irish acting 
dynasties with three productions that are truly family affairs 
on dec 5 laurence oliviers widow joan plowright opened at 
the old vic theater in a revival of jb priestleys time and the 
conways the cast includes the two olivier daughters tamsin and 
juliekate directed by their brother richard 
one week later dec 11 came the redgrave sisters vanessa and 
lynn in anton chekhovs the three sisters the opening at the 
queens theater marks their first stage appearance together 
the third sister is played by their 24yearold niece jemma 
redgrave the daughter of their actor brother corin jemma joins 
her cousins natasha and joely richardson in the fifth generation 
of acting redgraves 
chekhovs masterwork has already been seen in another family 
production in london this year that soldout production which 
ended sept 29 starred irelands cusack sisters sinead sorcha 
and niamh cusack and their father cyril 
while keenly aware that these ventures are vulnerable to charges 
of gimmickry all three families found the blood ties invigorating 
we were all very aware of the pitfalls says sorcha cusack 
thats why it took us so long to commit ourselves to doing it 
lynn redgrave says whatever we did together it had not to be 
a gimmick it had to be something that in any legitimate production 
anywhere we would have been thought of for those parts 
the productions have been warmly supported by audiences and 
critics though not without dissent 
lack of box office bankability singly is bolstered by the 
sheer gimmickiness of having all the family work together a sort 
of thinking mans osmonds snarled columnist julie burchill in 
the mail a sunday newspaper 
most commentators however were enthusiastic about productions 
that bring a lifetime of intimacy to the theater 
i just think that if youve got a vocabulary that goes back 40 
years as is the case with myself and sorcha theres no doubt at 
all that we have a given says sinead cusack 
its there in our bloodstream our very being which is to do 
with our umbilical cords 
sinead at age 42 the oldest cusack sister played masha the 
middle one of chekhovs trio sorcha 40 played the older olga 
niamh 30 played baby sister irina in a production that looks 
likely to transfer to new york in the new year 
lynn redgrave says her familys production resulted from a 
benefit performance on dec 10 1989 in new york where vanessa 
was finishing her broadway engagement in tennessee williams 
orpheus descending 
vanessa was organizing a concert called the wall breaks to 
benefit victims of stalins repression to conclude the first act 
she asked lynn sigourney weaver and christopher reeve to join her 
in a condensed version of the final scene of the three sisters 
i was full of nerves about it recalls lynn redgrave 47 
the younger sister by six years there was a real sort of quiet 
in the house and one realized here we were walking forward for 
the first time 
before long a project was born 
the minute we did the concert i knew this could work which 
is why we so wholeheartedly went into it she says 
the three sisters is actually the second sisters act for 
the redgraves 
four days before rehearsals began they completed a tv remake of 
the 1962 horror film whatever happened to baby jane its due 
to be aired in the united states on abc in february lynn inherits 
bette daviss role as the demented baby jane hudson with vanessa 
filling joan crawfords shoes as her crippled sister 
we havent spent this much consecutive time together since we 
were children laughs lynn redgrave who unlike vanessa has 
based most of her career in the united states its bringing back 
memories we havent had in ages 
but lynn says there were times when sibling undercurrents left 
off and chekhovs creations took over 
we feel very much that we are these characters or our version 
of these characters she says while were actually playing it 
the family links are a bit more amorphous 
sorcha cusack had a similar experience obviously when im 
working im not thinking whether its my sister or not my sister 
but of course they are my sisters thats something thats there 
for free i dont think about it 
in time and the conways written in 1937 joan plowright 
plays the matriarch presiding over a brood of kids two of whom are 
played by her and lord oliviers reallife daughters 
it can help well it does help a lot because you are 
dealing with people who are very close to you and all that feeling 
of familiarity is there for you says tamsin olivier 27 
but her 29yearold brother richard the plays director 
stresses that priestley was writing about the conways not the 
oliviers 
i wouldnt want people to family spot he says 
hopefully they come to see the play primarily and if they enjoy 
peoples performances then thats terrific 
next spring timothy west and prunella scales husband and wife 
in real life play the fraught tyrones in eugene oneills long 
days journey into night at the royal national theater no word 
yet on whether their son sam west an actor will play one of the 
tyrones two sons 
other family connections have yet to be explored 
maggie smith the tonywinning star of broadways lettice and 
lovage has two sons in drama school rosemary harris daughter 
jennifer ehle is in her last year at londons central school of 
speech and drama susannah york edward woodward and frank finlay 
each have children who have decided to act 
in the united states if famous families appear together at all 
its usually on the screen henry and jane fonda in on golden 
pond beau and jeff bridges in the fabulous baker boys the 
carradines quaids guests and keaches in the long riders 
