<TEXT>
 
guitar music of nicolo paganini europa frederic zigante 
 
paganini the demon of the violin who transformed the 
instruments technique and turned himself into legend was also an 
accomplished guitarist that is no secret nor the fact that he 
wrote numerous chamber works involving the guitar usually with 
violin 
but paganini 17821840 also wrote an astonishingly vast and 
until recently unknown number of solo works for the instrument a 
complete edition was not published until the mid1980s 150 years 
after they were written before then only 26 of his guitar pieces 
were available dating from a 1926 edition europa introduces most 
of this new richness of repertoire on four discs beautifully 
played by frederic zigante 
the pieces on the release break down into 40 sonatas five 
sonatinas 16 various onemovement works and 43 ghiribizzi or 
popular song transcriptions from mozart paganini himself and 
lesser composers of the day 
according to zigantes excellent notes paganini publicly never 
performed any of these though he might have planned to publish 
some during his lifetime because a small number survive in neat 
copies apparently prepared for a printer paganini was also 
famously protective of his manuscripts when concertizing around 
europe he would personally distribute and retrieve the orchestra 
parts to his concertos for fear of pirated editions 
because he rarely played the guitar in public and because he 
learned it pretty much on his own paganini developed his own 
guitar technique zigante points out that he doesnt use the 
progression of positions of standard 19thcentury technique and 
writes music that is horizontal in nature more like a violin and 
less like vertical chordal writing more typical of the instrument 
many of paganinis violinistic tendencies can be heard 
arpeggios beginning phrases sudden register changes leaps and 
fast scales but more striking are the large number of simpler 
pieces with easy flowing melodies and naturalsounding 
accompaniment 
zigantes playing matches his scholarship he has a warm sound 
and lyrical manner and keeps an obvious affection for this music 
despite recording more than 100 pieces totaling four hours and 20 
minutes by the same composer 
it is a wealth of excellent music for classical guitar lovers 
and listeners partial to 19thcentury italian melody one hopes it 
will spur interest in paganinis guitar output and prompt more live 
performances of it by guitarists 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
 
triple threat alligator records lucky peterson 
 
a 20plusyear career would denote senior status for many 
performers bluesman lucky petersons 20plus years of performing 
leave him in his mid20s with 20plus years to go a musical 
prodigy at 3 peterson is emerging as a young ambassador of the 
blues robert cray may have the name recognition and the big record 
label contract but peterson is one to watch 
triple threat petersons second effort for alligator 
records and his fourth solo lp is an excellent showcase for the 
multitalented native of buffalo ny peterson massages the 
keyboards with the same soul that wells up out of his big voice 
for proof listen to im free youll also hear the third of 
petersons triple threats his fine guitar playing 
where cray has shaped his earlier raw sounds to draw more 
commercial appeal peterson still revels in the edginess of a 
tough urban beat but theres a healthy dose of soul running 
through the record theres also great potential for peterson to 
take his ambassadorship across the line of commercialism ala cray 
and spread the word of the blues 
lyrics on triple threat dont grab hold of your shortterm 
memory like more commercial music does youre not likely to find 
yourself repeating dont cloud up on me if you aint going to 
rain in the shower but for that weakness the record is a great 
mix of funky soul and blues with a beat 
by james reindl associated press writer 
