<TEXT>
a cultural thaw opened the way but it took 
10 years to put together a show of long stored masks weapons and 
ceremonial clothes used by the peoples of the frigid lands on both 
sides of the bering strait 
crossroads of continents cultures of siberia and alaska is 
a smithsonian institution traveling exhibit now at the gene autry 
western heritage museum in griffith park 
the idea for the exhibit of about 600 cultural artifacts arose 
as a bridge between the soviet union and the united states but the 
project endured some chilly times before the recent dramatic 
improvement in relations 
we were delayed because of political problems the exhibits 
curator william w fitzhugh said in an interview from his office 
in washington 
we were fighting against the image of the evil empire we 
were the test wave of glasnost said fitzhugh who is director of 
the smithsonians center for arctic studies 
sergei serov fitzhughs soviet counterpart and senior 
researcher with leningrads institute of ethnology said the 
project went well at their level we experienced no problems with 
cooperation between scholars he said 
the monumental task of uniting collections from the two 
countries started in 1978 when the soviet union became more 
receptive to scholarly exchanges fitzhugh said 
if you take a project of this geographic scope immensity you 
need time just to get familiar with the objects he said 
documentation takes many many hours and we had no funding from 
any american corporations 
fitzhugh and his team made several trips to the soviet union 
and russian researchers made similar trips here 
in musty dusty corners of museum warehouses attics and 
basements fitzhugh found items he had only read about from the 
years before the united states bought alaska from russia in 1867 
we were rediscovering collections that long had been in 
storage he said 
it is quite a task to pack to mount to dismount and check 
all the items and do condition checks and damage checks said 
serov we have been lucky that nothing has been seriously 
damaged 
enthusiasts who attend the display of jewelry ivory work 
masks religious costumes and everyday items like hunting and 
fishing tools walk into darkened rooms that create an arctic winter 
atmosphere 
the lighting is subdued due to the fragility of the artifacts 
some a century old the pieces are sensitive to light and could be 
permanently damaged if exposed 
the artifacts are made with vegetable and animal dyes and the 
peoples who created them were accustomed to throwing them away 
after they were used fitzhugh said 
things made for everyday use were expendable after a couple of 
months he added 
one example of the elaborate work is a siberian bucket made from 
the jawbone of a whale using bentwood techniques the jaw was 
soaked bent riveted and fastened to a wooden bottom the 
ornamental trim decorated the handle of what was believed to be a 
chamber pot 
the exhibit was unveiled in 1988 at the national museum of 
natural history in washington it also was displayed in seattle and 
new york in 1989 and was shown earlier this year in indianapolis 
it will be at the western heritage museum until feb 24 then it 
will move on to the anchorage museum of history and art in alaska 
and the canadian museum of civilization in ottawa 
in 1992 organizers hope to take the exhibit to the soviet union 
to cities including moscow leningrad and novosibirsk 
museum visitors who crave more soviet art can view the work of 
eight russian artists at the lori kaye gallery in garden grove the 
exhibit which opened nov 29 includes 40 watercolors by vasil 
panikarov most of them still lifes enabling him to escape the 
gloomy russian everyday life 
the exhibit also includes the window by the late alexander 
freyidin whose works are considered national treasures and 
restricted from leaving the country 
the other artists with works in the show are constantin filatov 
victor resovich lev michaelovich shmoys gavzdinskaya natalya 
teodorvna tchulvaloma and vera alexandra tchiyka 
another soviet exhibit keepers of the flame was organized 
by selma holo director of the university of southern californias 
fisher gallery open until jan 19 it will be taken to three other 
college campus galleries 
keepers of the flame is a show of 25 unofficial or 
underground artists before the era of glasnost artists who did 
not qualify to join the official artists union were not recognized 
and banned from public exhibit in 1975 the kgb dismantled an 
outdoor show of such art 
lori kaye said the soviet artists view of life is very 
different 
just getting art supplies in the soviet union is a test of an 
artists commitment to the craft she said 
paper is often crude and causes the watercolors to react very 
differently she said the paints themselves are difficult to 
find and often have to be made using oldfashioned techniques such 
as squeezing the oils from flower petals 
</TEXT>
