<TEXT>
the great gatsby is still one of geoffrey 
wolffs favorite books and narrator nick carraways insistence 
that he is inclined to reserve all judgments still makes the 
author laugh 
the novel is nothing but judgments wolff insists a young mans 
moral education carraway never stops evaluating gatsby or daisy or 
tom buchanan or himself he has an opinion on everything and his 
opinion is constantly shifting 
but wolff doesnt mean that as criticism he considers carraway 
the perfect writer an inspiration for his own books a man who 
both observes and participates making judgments and then changing 
them is part of the process a moral education for an author who 
learns something new with every word 
were told teachers tell us show dont tell show dont 
tell show dont tell i dont feel comfortable only showing i do 
want to tell when i have a judgment to sound off on wolff 
author of the duke of deception memories of my father 
providence and the new the final club said in an 
interview 
i think some things are right and some things are wrong i 
like to say when i think this person shouldnt have done something 
even at the oldfashioned primitive level that violates all the 
aesthetics for better or worse i feel thats something ive been 
doing 
the final club alfred a knopf 1995 is narrated by 
nathaniel clay a princeton university student class of 60 who 
leaves behind a troubled family life in seattle 
his education begins immediately on the eastbound empire 
builder train when he meets the beautiful diana pronounced 
deeahnah she emphasizes carr falling madly in love with a 
