<TEXT>
world trade officials opened a final 
round of global trade talks today with a blunt reminder that the 
economic health of millions was riding on the outcome of their 
bargaining 
the world is expecting a great deal of you belgian prime 
minister wilfried martens told the delegates from nations attending 
the negotiating session of the 107nation uruguay round the most 
ambitious trade talks ever 
failure would deal world trade stability a nasty blow and 
would seriously harm the world economy he said at the heysel 
palaces exhibition complex on the outskirts of the belgian capital 
trade officials said 1650 officials from 96 nations were in 
attendance to launch the week of bargaining which has been 
threatened with failure by an acrimonious fight over cuts in 
government payments to farmers 
the dispute has pitted the european community and japan against 
the united states australia and others 
today the united states formally warned it may impose 
prohibitive tariffs on some imports from the european community 
unless the ec agrees to renew an accord on compensation for 
potential losses of us farm exports to spain and portugal 
us trade officials said the move could cost the 12nation 
community almost 420 million in exports 
thousands of farmers mostly europeans marched through brussels 
to show their opposition to any move to trim their support 
payments 
the negotiations which began in 1986 in the uruguayan resort of 
punta del este are designed to lower barriers to trade in 15 
areas including agriculture textiles manufactured goods and 
services such as banking transportation telecommunications and 
construction 
indonesias trade minister arifin siregar complained today 
that rich nations were hindering work on an overall agreement 
with a few days left in the uruguay round we are being 
confronted with a crisis situation mainly attributed to roadblocks 
put up by the majors he told the opening session 
he said if the problems were not solved quickly it would not 
be an exaggeration to say that the decay of the multilateral 
trading system has begun 
