<TEXT>
the patent and trademark office today 
recognized an aroma as a subject for trademark registration for the 
first time it granted a trademark to the scent of a line of 
embroidery yarns and threads 
the office approved registration of a scent described by its 
developer celia clarke of goleta calif as a highimpact 
fresh floral fragrance reminiscent of plumeria blossoms 
ms clarkes application was initially turned down on grounds 
the products fragrance did not qualify for a trademark the ruling 
was overturned on sept 19 by the trademark trial and appeal board 
this marks the first time in the history of trademarks that a 
fragrance has been approved for registration said jeffrey m 
samuels assistant commissioner for trademarks we are all 
familiar with what trademarks look like now well see what they 
smell like 
approval of the registration was published in todays trademark 
official gazette members of the public have 30 days in which to 
oppose registration if no opposition is filed the registration 
will be issued on feb 26 
more than one million trademarks have been registered since the 
first trademark law was passed in 1870 about 600000 of them are 
still in use a trademark registration lasts 10 years and can be 
renewed indefinitely 
david sams chairman of the trademark trial and appeal board 
said ms clarke and her associates maintained that the fragrance 
was in fact the trademark by which their product could be 
distinguished from other peoples thread and yarn 
sams said the boards reasoning in granting the application was 
that there was no natural fragrance to yarn and no evidence that 
it was a common practice or a practice of anybody else at all in 
the industry to make their yarn scented so that it stood out and 
was distinctive to this particular producer of yarn 
he said the board said in a footnote to its decision that it was 
not passing any judgment on registerability of a scent or 
fragrance on products which are noted for those features like 
perfumes and household products we left for another day whether a 
party could register a particular scent for a product sold for its 
scent 
we are here talking about an unusual application of a scent to 
a product sams said 
ms clarke reached by telephone in goleta said the firm a 
manufacturer of punch embroidery needles has been in business 15 
years she said the application for trademark was submitted about 
two years ago when the company began producing the scented yarn 
we are a small company so we havent done a big lot with it 
although we do intend to she said i think we will really push 
it now and show it more she said 
