a judge on monday tightened the terms of bail 
for indicted financier charles h keating jr after prosecutors 
complained that the former lincoln savings and loan owner couldnt 
be found over the thanksgiving weekend 
superior court judge lance ito ordered the district attorneys 
office and keatings attorneys to set up a schedule specifying the 
day and hour at which keating can be reached by telephone each 
week 
the order differs from one set earlier by a federal judge by 
establishing the specific time for a call 
that way you dont have to play phone tag with each other 
ito said 
keating free on 300000 bail is charged with 46 counts of 
fraud alleging he misled investors into believing that highyield 
highrisk bonds issued by the lincoln parent american continental 
corp were safe the indictment says buyers many of them elderly 
people investing their life savings lost some 200 million 
the bonds became worthless in april 1989 when american 
continental sought bankruptcy protection lincoln was seized the 
following day by federal regulators experts say its failure will 
cost taxpayers 2 billion the largest savings and loan bailout to 
date 
ito postponed until jan 11 discussion of an amended indictment 
that revises 20 of 42 original counts against keating and adds four 
counts 
