<DOCNO> AP901203-0260 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
steel importers have taken a bad rap for 
dumping products in the united states when the real culprit is 
volatility in world currency markets a trade group said monday 
the american institute for imported steel contended that the 
price discrepancies often seen in foreign steel are in many 
instances due to unpredictable changes in the dollars value 
against foreign currencies 
in recent months the dollar has fluctuated dramatically on world 
currenyy markets amid a weakening of the us economy and the 
growing potential for war in the persian gulf 
under present antidumping rules throughout the world 
international traders can become targets of expensive litigation 
for reasons entirely beyond their control said john griffin the 
institutes president at a news conference in new york where the 
group was holding an annual meeting 
dumping is the practice of selling foreign goods at unfairly 
low prices in order to grab a bigger share of the market it is 
considered a violation of import rules in the united states and 
many other countries 
there has been widespread concern in the steel industry about 
what domestic producers call foreign dumping of steel in the united 
states once one of the worlds mightiest steelmakers but now a 
major importer 
to remedy what it called a potentially serious problem the 
steelimport institute proposed an agreement under which 
governments apply a 10year average to exchange rates to be used in 
calculating costs and prices 
the proposal an amendment to existing antidumping rules would 
strengthen the law by sharpening focus on truly predatory acts of 
international price discrimination unrelated to shifting exchange 
rates said griffin 
it was unclear if the proposal would win the necessary 
international support backers hope to introduce it in negotiations 
next year 
institute members said dumping accusations were worsening with 
the dollars recent plunge in value which were increasing imported 
steels dollar value but not giving the price charged in the united 
states enough time to catch up 
as a result steel importers are being accused of technical 
dumping in cases brought against them by us steel manufacturers 
group members said 
american companies brought roughly 395 cases against importers 
between 1980 and 1989 a dramatic increase from earlier years said 
kermit almstedt an attorney representing the trade group 
almstedt said he did not know how many of those lawsuits were 
prompted by technical dumping but added one of the reasons 
youre seeing a lot of cases against the japanese is a result of 
the exchange rates 
importers found charging unfairly low prices for their products 
can be slapped with a tarrif equal to the difference between what 
they charged and the products perceived fair market price 
almstedt said 
steel importers fear a big litigation problem in 1992 with 
president bushs planned lifting of the system of voluntary 
restraint agreements which for the past five years has curbed 
imports of steel from most major supplying countries into the 
united states 
the potential for a subsequent flood of steel imports into the 
united states could prompt a backlash from domestic steel 
manufacturers members said 
</TEXT>
