<TEXT>
atlantic richfield co sued more than 70 
insurance carriers for reimbursement of the huge costs of restoring 
50 hazardous waste sites polluted over six decades company 
officials said monday 
experts said the case will help set precedents for insurers and 
companies nationwide it stems from a california supreme court 
ruling two weeks ago that the cost of cleaning up toxic pollution 
is part of the damages to be paid by insurers under standard 
comprehensive general liability policies 
arco the big los angelesbased oil company also is asking to 
have the duties and liabilities of both companies and insurers 
clarified under the state supreme court ruling 
arco believes that this action will bring the questions of 
insurance coverage and compensation before a single forum for 
orderly and efficient resolution and administration arco said in 
a statement 
supreme courts in massachusetts minnesota washington and north 
carolina have made similar rulings in recent months 
thecase decided nov 15 said insurance companies that provide 
property coverage must pay their policyholders costs of cleaning 
up toxic waste at government order the case was brought against 
aiu insurance co and other insurers after fmc a chicagobased 
chemical and weapons company was sued by federal and local 
agencies for allegedly polluting land and water at 79 sites in a 
number of states 
the unanimous state supreme court ruling was broad but not 
allinclusive carriers have legal defenses that include gross 
negligence or willful misconduct by the insured many recent 
policies also exclude all but sudden and accidental instances 
of pollution 
companies affected by superfund legislation all over the nation 
are checking old policies to see if they can escape liability for 
increasingly expensive toxic cleanup work said joel moskowitz a 
partner specializing in environmental law with the gibson dunn amp 
crutcher firm in los angeles 
steve wasdick a spokesman for aetna casualty and surety co of 
america said suits over toxic waste liability have frequently 
wound up in court and often turn on the language of the policy by 
the early 1970s many carriers included pollution exclusion 
clauses to avoid liability except when an incident was sudden and 
accidental 
there have been a good number that have gone the insurers way 
too wasdick said 
among the carriers named as defendants in arcos lawsuit are 
aetna firemans fund insurance travelers insurance lloyds of 
london and more than 20 other foreign companies 
the defendants issued policies as far back as the 1930s to arco 
and its predecessor companies anaconda co richfield oil corp 
sinclair oil corp and atlantic refining co 
arco spokesman albert greenstein said its too early to predict 
the effect of the companys suit filed nov 23 because the 
supreme court ruling opened new ground 
greenstein also said its too early to tell the total costs of 
the cleanups it goes back so far and involves so many cases that 
its impossible to say he said 
the us environmental protection agency estimates the average 
costs of cleaning up a superfund site has grown from 9 million to 
25 million during the past five years however a recent study by 
the rand corp think tank in santa monica found that the vast 
majority cost far less than that 
