<DOCNO> AP901203-0269 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a smell can be registered as a trademark just 
as a word name symbol color or sound can be the patent and 
trademark office said in a groundbreaking decision monday 
the office approved registration of the scent of a type of 
embroidery yarn and sewing thread produced by clarkes osewez 
pronounced oh sew easy of goleta calif 
according to an exhibit in the case the yarn can be used to 
make among other things a scented skunk 
if nobody objects within 30 days the registration will be 
issued on feb 26 
a trademark is defined by law as any word name symbol or 
device or any combination of such things that is used to 
distinguish a product from the products sold or manufactured by 
others 
in an earlier case the color pink was recognized as a trademark 
for a type of fiberglass insulation the trademark was granted in 
the mid1980s to the owenscorning corp whose fiberglas product 
is pink 
sound marks such as the nbc chimes also have been registered 
there had not previously been a case however in which a 
trademark was granted for an aroma 
we are all familiar with what trademarks look like said 
jeffrey m samuels assistant commissioner for trademarks now 
well see what they smell like 
what this one smells like said celia clarke of clarkes osewez 
is a high impact fresh floral fragrance reminiscent of 
plumeria blossoms 
trademark examining attorney david cline had refused the 
registration on grounds that consumers were likely to regard the 
scent as just a pleasant feature of the yarn and not an indication 
of its origin 
ms clarke argued that customers dealers and distributors 
throughout the embroidery field recognized the firm as the source 
of scented embroidery yarn and thread 
she submitted as part of the record a kit containing yarn and 
thread for making a scented skunk 
the trademark trial and appeal board in a decision handed down 
sept 19 said ms clarke was the only person who had marketed 
yarns and threads with a fragrance 
under the circumstances of this case we see no reason why a 
fragrance is not capable of serving as a trademark to identify and 
distinguish a certain kind of product the board said 
it should be noted that we are not here talking about the 
registrability of scents or fragrances of products which are noted 
for those features such as perfumes colognes or scented household 
products it added in a footnote 
oscar mastin a spokesman for the patent and trademark office 
said perfumes can be patented and their names registered as 
trademarks 
j david sams chairman of the board said the case was the 
first in which copyright registration had been sought for a scent 
the company advertises its product as clarkes distinctive 
sofscented yarns they are of the type known in the trade as 
russian embroidery or punch embroidery 
ms clarke reached by telephone in goleta said the firm a 
manufacturer of punch embroidery needles has been in business 15 
years she said the application for trademark was submitted about 
two years ago when the company began producing the scented yarn 
we are a small company so we havent done a big lot with it 
although we do intend to she said i think we will really push 
it now and show it more 
more than 1 million trademarks have been registered since the 
first trademark law was passed in 1870 about 600000 of them are 
still in use a trademark registration lasts 10 years and can be 
renewed indefinitely 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

