<TEXT>
businesses facing lawsuits over pensions 
received some protection from the supreme court monday as the 
justices ruled workers cannot sue in state courts on grounds they 
were fired so their employers would not have to pay pension 
benefits 
the court ruled unanimously that state suits are preempted by 
the employee retirement income security act of 1974 which is aimed 
at assuring that workers get their retirement pay 
state lawsuits had loomed as potentially far more lucrative 
because fired employees could win punitive damages that greatly 
exceed lost pay 
in other cases affecting businesses the supreme court on 
monday 
left intact an iowa supreme court ruling that forced four 
omaha neb automobile dealerships to defend themselves in iowa 
courts in lawsuits brought under that states consumer fraud laws 
the dealerships had argued that iowas courts have no authority 
over them 
ruled that a federal anticounterfeiting law may be used to 
crack down on the sale of used cars with phony mileage readings 
writing in the pension case justice sandra day oconnor said 
congress clearly intended to preclude state lawsuits over firings 
motivated by efforts to avoid paying pension benefits 
the goal was to minimize the administrative and financial 
burden of complying with conflicting directives among states or 
between states and the federal government oconnor said 
the decision is a victory for the ingersollrand co which was 
sued by perry mcclendon after it fired him in 1982 
mcclendon had been transferred by the company from san antonio 
to dallas in 1979 to develop a sales market for construction 
equipment there he was fired four months before his 10th 
anniversary with the company 
a worker with 10 years experience is entitled to have his 
pension vested which meant ingersollrand would have to contribute 
to mcclendons retirement benefits 
mcclendon sued in texas state courts accusing his former 
employer of firing him to avoid paying pension benefits the 
company said he was fired to reduce the workforce and save money 
mcclendon did not sue for lost pension benefits in fact 
shortly after he sued the company agreed to vest his pension 
instead mcclendons suit sought a potentially bigmoney judgment 
for lost wages mental anguish and punitive damages 
</TEXT>
