<TEXT>
the government said monday it hopes to 
halve state ownership of businesses in the next few years as it 
replaces the marxist economic model of past communist rulers with 
one where private ownership dominates 
we may succeed in reducing the share of state ownership to 50 
percent or less in the coming three to four years government 
official lajos csepi told reporters 
csepi is managing director of the state property agency set up 
in march as hungary prepared for the first democratic elections in 
four decades to oversee the sale of stateowned assets 
he spoke on the eve of a scheduled national address by premier 
jozsef antall expected to deal primarily with the dismal state of 
the economy the 1991 budget to be presented in parliament next 
week envisages a deficit of 78 billion forints or 13 billion 
as in other east european countries liberated from communist 
domination this year initial euphoria among the population has 
been replaced by gloom over the economic picture as the nation 
struggles to correct past mistakes 
inflation is at 35 percent the foreign debt has reached 20 
billion the highest per capita among former soviet bloc nations 
unemployment officially unknown under the communist leadership is 
now at 70000 and is expected to balloon to 200000 of the 45 
million work force by next year poverty is growing 
the state mti news agency cited statistics indicating that at 
least 60 percent of families are drawing on savings just to make 
ends meet compared to 40 percent last year 
growing frustration peaked late last month in a threeday 
national blockade of main streets and highways by truckers and 
cabbies irate over a planned 65percent gasoline price hike 
most of the population supported the unprecedented protest 
forcing antalls conservative government coalition to back down and 
agree to lesser price increases 
the decision to increase gasoline prices was due in part to 
shortfalls in promised soviet oil deliveries and to the rising 
price of crude on the world market because of the gulf crisis 
janos martonyi state secretary of the ministry of international 
economic relations recently estimated economic damage from the 
gulf crisis at 200 million including the cancellation of trade 
with iraq under terms of a un embargo 
worsening economic conditions have taken their toll on 
government popularity with hungarians increasingly agreeing with 
opposition charges that the return to a capitalist economy is being 
mismanaged and is taking too long 
the criticism has exacerbated internal government differences 
finance minister ferenc rabar announced oct 10 that he planned to 
resign after passage of the budget following months of dispute 
with gyoergy matolcsi state secretary of the prime ministers 
office and a key economic aide over responsibility for longterm 
economic plans 
