littlejohn said the locals members want the 400000 divided 
among the 96 workers who lost their jobs after the july 19 
explosion basf said it would pay for tuition at vocational 
schools books and living expenses 
the blast blamed on explosive fumes from a cleaning solvent 
destroyed much of the plant which made chemicals to coat paper 
cups and food cans the explosion killed two people and injured 
about 80 others 
the federal occupational safety and health administration fined 
the company 16 million in november citing more than 100 safety 
violations at the plant 
while our actions can in no way make up for the hardships 
caused by the accident we have tried to do as much as we can and 
we will continue to do so said j larry jameson president of 
basfs coatings and colorings division 
a threemember panel including an administrator from the 
university of cincinnati is to supervise a trust fund to pay for 
the workers training the company said 
