<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901203-0285 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
publisher james hoge said monday he is 
determined to lure advertisers and readers back to the 
strikehampered daily news and expects the tabloid to survive and 
thrive 
absolutely no question about it hoge said in an interview 
we will prevail we hope through settlement but if not without 
it 
the man at the center of the 5weekold strike by 2100 
unionized employees said he is exploring options to take the paper 
in new directions once the work force is stabilized 
before new plans can be carried out he said the strike must 
end profits must begin and the work abuses the news has alleged 
must be eliminated 
as he sat in his eighthfloor office in midtown manhattan hoge 
spoke as if addressing the picketers on the sidewalk below 
fellows get rid of the inefficiencies with us so we can build a 
secure future for the next century 
the news recently spent 3 million to 4 million to select new 
technology and design new printing plants to be built on land 
bought in new jersey and long island before the strike the 
publisher said 
he said expansion options being weighed include creating either 
an afternoon edition a satelliteproduced national edition or a 
school edition at least one was discussed at a monday morning 
meeting he said but he gave no further details 
i wouldnt want to put a time on it now hoge said we 
have been chomping at the bit to be innovative and try to do things 
when we think its practical to do so and that includes variations 
on what we do today 
the strike by nine unions which began oct 25 has cost the 
paper untold millions of dollars it has been marked by incidents 
of vandalism against news trucks and against news dealers who carry 
the paper 
the unions say the news engaged in unfair labor practices which 
the paper denies and the news parent the tribune co of chicago 
is trying to break the unions a charge hoge denied monday 
major advertisers have deserted the pages of what was before 
the strike the nations thirdlargest metropolitan daily and have 
fattened the pages of its tabloid rivals 
hoge estimated the papers losses would total 200 million from 
1979 to the end of this year but he would not specify how much the 
strike is costing the news vice president for human resources 
john t sloan has said the paper expects to lose 30 million to 
35 million in this quarter 
the paper has published every day during the strike using 
management replacement workers and employees who crossed the 
picket line but circulation which was 109 million on weekdays 
before the strike has dropped drastically 
the news filed a civil racketeering suit against the striking 
unions last week claiming a pattern of orchestrated violence had 
blocked the papers distribution 
the paper has used a system of hawkers numbering more than 
1000 to help sell the paper 
under an agreement reached with the metropolitan transportation 
authority and enforced by court order hawkers appeared monday on 
subway platforms and at commuter rail stations transit police said 
there were no violent incidents 
hoge said the hawkers each day are given their 200000 papers 
free and are making 100 percent profit that helps bring current 
circulation to 525000 hoge said 
here it is a question of building back arduously piece by 
piece the distribution system and we are doing it hoge said 
we went from about 400 sales outlets in the first 72 hours after 
the strike to well over 4000 now we added over 900 last week 
well add more this week 
hoge said he wants to get all parties to the negotiating table 
and is willing to offer job buyouts if the unions are interested 
however he reiterated the news demand for an end to what it sees 
as featherbedding and other labor abuses 
i do not regret at all that we have in this generation faced 
up to the issue that you have got to reform the contracts 
because if we did not the paper could not survive hoge said 
